<HEADLINE> Third Phase Construction of Shenhua Project Starts in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 9 (Xinhua) -- China's State Council has
recently approved the third-phase construction of the huge Shenhua
Project for coal shipment in north China.
</P>
<P>
The third-phase construction of Shenhua, a passage
to transport coal from western to eastern China, includes a 586-km
railway from Shuozhou city in Shanxi province to Huanghua city in
Hebei province and a port in Huanghua with an annual handling
capacity of 30 million tons.
</P>
<P>
An official source said that the third phase of the project is
scheduled to be completed by 2005.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Li Peng wrote for the project: "Speed up
construction of the Shuozhou-Huanghua Railway and the Huanghua
Port, and build the country's second-largest west-east passage for
coal shipment."
</P>
<P>
The Shenhua Project, with an investment of nearly 90 billion
yuan, includes construction of coal mines, a railway, power
plants, and a port. When completed, the railway will have an
annual hauling capacity of 100 million tons of coal.
</P>
<P>
The project will play an important role in stepping up energy
development in western China and in ensuring energy supplies in
eastern and southern China.
</P>
<P>
The Shuozhou-Huanghua Railway is expected to be linked to the
north-south Beijing-Kowloon Railway by 2000. And, the Huanghua
Port will have a yearly handling capacity of 60 million tons in
future.
</P>
<P>
By 2003, the Huanghua Port will build four 35,000-ton
deep-water berths.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
