<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One in Ten British Young Children Suffer Brain Damage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 9 (Xinhua)-- One in ten British young children
are suffering brain damage from lead pollution, The Independent On
Sunday reported today.
</P>
<P>
The intelligence of over 440,000 of children under six has been
diminished by exposure to the toxic metal at a time when their
brains are developing, the newspaper quoted a report to be
published this week as saying.
</P>
<P>
The report, by Dr Erik Millstone, Senior Lecturer at Sussex
University says that British government have been negligent and
culpable in doing little to tackle the two main causes of this
exposure, lead in paint and drinking water.
</P>
<P>
It says some 10 million homes receive drinking water through
lead piping, either within the house or in the water company's
system, or both.
</P>
<P>
Britain allows 50 micrograms of lead per litre of water, five
times the level recommended by the World Health Organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
