<HEADLINE> S. Africa Deports 15,000 Zimbabweans This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 9 (Xinhua) -- Some 15,735 Zimbabweans who had
been illegally settled in South Africa, were deported between
January to October this year, the South African Home Affairs
Office said today.
</P>
<P>
Seventy-six more Zimbabweans involved in criminal activities
ranging from theft, robbery, murder, fraud, housebreaking to
possession of protected game were also deported during the same
period, the Zimbabwe News Agency quoted the South African Home
Affairs Office as reporting.
</P>
<P>
The South African Home Affairs Office said, " The majority of
illegal persons residing in South Africa enter clandestinely and
so it is difficult to quantify the number of illegal settlers."
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe and South Africa had started bilateral talks in an
effort to curb the flow of illegal migrants while border control
measures were also being stepped up.
</P>
<P>
A survey conducted in 1995 estimated that between 2.5 and 4.1
million illegal migrants resided in South Africa were attracted
by the better economy and working conditions.
</P>
<P>
South Africa sees a large number of illegal settlers from
Zimbabwe and Mozambique who were picked up during police raids.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to reduce the number of illegal aliens, South Africa
introduced new and stricter visa regulations in November 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
