<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges UN to Take Strong Action against Saddam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 9 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton has
urged the United Nations to take "very strong and unambiguous
action" against Iraqi President Saddam Hussein so that he could
comply with U.N. weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
"I expect the United Nations to take very strong and
unambiguous action to make it perfectly clear he has to comply
... If he doesn't comply then the world community will have to
take some action," Clinton said in an interview, taped after he
met his top foreign policy advisers on Saturday and released on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi government has turned away U.N. weapons inspection
teams that included Americans in nine consecutive days. And
Clinton said he would not be bullied by Iraqi President Saddam's
defiance.
</P>
<P>
Asked if a military strike against Iraq was necessary, Clinton
said: "I don't want to rule anything in or out. I think it's -- at
a moment like this -- it's very important that the president
maintain all options. And that's where I want to be."
</P>
<P>
"But I think that Saddam Hussein needs to understand that this
is a serious business and this is not just the president of the
United States," he added.
</P>
<P>
Clinton called on Arab nations and U.N. Security Council
members Russia and France to support the U.N. in order to present
a united front in dealing with Saddam Hussein. Russia and France
have been reluctant to take military action against Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
