<HEADLINE> Ex-UN Chief Urges Non-stop of UN-Iraq Dialog </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 9 (Xinhua) -- Former United Nations Secretary
General Boutros Boutros Ghali today called on the UN and Iraq to
maintain their dialog to avoid the outbreak of new confrontations.
</P>
<P>
Ghali was speaking to reporters here before leaving for Hanoi
to take part in the Francophone summit due to open on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The veteran Egyptian diplomat urged the world community to take
into consideration of sufferings of the Iraqi people before any
decision is made.
</P>
<P>
"The Iraqis, in fact, are the ones who are suffering from the
economic sanctions imposed on the country and who will also be
victimized by any additional military sanctions which could be
imposed on Iraq," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is threatening to take action against Iraq following
Iraq's decision last week to expel Americans from the UN Special
Committee in charge of scrapping Iraqi weapons of mass destruction
under terms of the 1991 Gulf War ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
Iraq says it has done well in cooperating with U.N. inspectors
and wants the easing of the crippling sanctions imposed after the
Gulf War. Rejecting Baghdad's claims, the U.S. led a campaign two
weeks ago in the U.N. Security Council to pass a resolution
threatening further sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Ghali, who is vying for a nomination as the Francophone
Secretary General, said he now enjoys the support of various
African, European and Latin American states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
