<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-09 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Leaders Promise Reply on Settlements, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 9 (Xinhua) -- Israeli leaders today
stressed that Israel would give its reply on the contentious
issues of suspension of its settlements and implementation of
further troop pullouts in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Both Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Foreign
Minister David Levy made the announcement during today's weekly
Cabinet meeting, which was briefed on the just-concluded peace
talks held with the Palestinian side in Washington early this week.
</P>
<P>
Levy defended his talks with Palestinian Leader Yasser Arafat's
deputy Mahmoud Abbas (Abu Mazen), saying both sides have agreed to
more work to deal with various issues in the interim accords,
including the suspension of Jewish settlement and troop
redeployments.
</P>
<P>
"It's impossible to think that we will return from Washington
with an agreement that wraps everything up," he was quoted by the
the Cabinet satement as saying.
</P>
<P>
Levy added Israel would have to give a reply on the issues of
settlement time-out and further troop redeployments.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu told the cabinet that efforts would continue to try
to work out a settlement on the above-mentioned issues despite the
difference of opinions between Israel and the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
But he stressed that Israel would stand by its position that
"the right thing to do is to enter the final-status talks."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has been floating the idea of entering the
final-status talks by bypassing the difficult phase of the
interim stage, in order to wrap up a final settlement on all
issues. The PNA has rejected the proposal and insists on Israel's
implementation of the interim accords.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's office today issued an update on the schedule of
his upcoming visit to Britain and the United States, confirming
his meeting with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on
Friday in London before heading to the U.S. on Sunday
morning. Netanyahu is to attend the conference of the Federations
of Jewish Organizations in the U.S. and Canada held in
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
But the update still fell short of announcing the much-expected
meeting between Netanyahu and U.S. President Bill Clinton, who is
reportedly refusing to see Netanyahu because of his disappointment
with the slow pace of the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the Netanyahu-Clinton summit would
probably be set up by Netanyahu's meeting with Albright in
London. In his comments, Netanyahu only said his meeting with
Clinton would be arranged in coordination between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Israel and the PNA have different assessments of the results
of the Washington talks held under the auspices of the
U.S. government. While Levy hailed the talks as a "great
progress" in providing a good atmosphere for future talks, Arafat
described them as a failure that achieved nothing.
</P>
<P>
Although the nine joint Israeli-Palestinian interim committees
resumed their work today, Israeli officials have downplayed the
prospect of quick progress in the talks, citing that only
Netanyahu would have the authority to make concessions on the
most controversial issues of settlements and further troop
pullouts.
</P>
<P>
Analysts expected Albright to pressure Netanyahu to ease down
his tough stance on continuing settlement expansion, in order to
pave the way for progress in the peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
