<HEADLINE> Leather Technology Institute to Be Set up in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, November 9 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian government
planed to construct a leather technology institute to overcome
the shortage of trained manpower in the industry, Ethiopian
Minister of Trade and Industry Kassahun Ayele has said.
</P>
<P>
The minister made the remarks Saturday at an inaugural
ceremony of a tannery in Mojo Town, 70 kms southeast of the
Ethiopian capital.
</P>
<P>
Preparations are underway for the construction of the
institute which will come into operation next year, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the Ethiopian government will give all
the necessary support to entrepreneurs who want to engage in
modern leather industry and export of leather products.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia is one of the biggest animal husbandry nations in
Africa with a total of 130 million domestic animals, including 27
million cattle, 42 million sheep and goats, 52 million pigs,
seven million horses and one million camels.
</P>
<P>
The new tannery which can process 3,000 pieces of skins daily
was built at a cost of 1.32 million U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
