<DOCNO> XIE19971110.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Merger Value Reachs Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, November 9 (Xinhua) -- The value of Worldwide company
mergers has reached a record high of 760 billion U.S. dollars so
far this year, the New York Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The dollar value of mergers grew each year since 1993 when it
stood at only over 200 billion dollars, a U.S. consulting firm
Securities Data Corporation was quoted by the Times as saying.
</P>
<P>
Based on its survey, the Computer Science Corporation (CSC)
Index, another U.S. consulting company said a successful merger
could be the one aimed at consolidation in which a dominant player
folds smaller companies into its already finely tuned machine.
</P>
<P>
Other successful cases include pioneering mergers in which two
companies unite to enter a market neither was equipped to enter
alone, and talent-scout mergers in which one company buys another
to obtain access to its people, patents or processes.
</P>
<P>
CSC Index found a difference in financing patterns between
mergers in the 1980's and today. Previously, many of the acquirers
financed their deals through debt, but today's deals are generally
financed with stock or cash.
</P>
<P>
The debt pattern was proven vulnerable to financial turmoil in
the 80's as many of the companies were unable to meet their debt
payments without slashing staff and operating budgets or selling
aspects at rock-bottom prices.
</P>
<P>
Companies have learned to avoid the risks of overpayment and
they tend to be more successful than those in the 80's, analysts
say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
