<DOCNO> XIE19971110.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CBI Survey Confirms Clear Majority for EMU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BIRMINGHAM, November 9 (Xinhua) - A clear majority of CBI
(Confederation of British Industry) members support the principle
of UK membership of Economic and Monetary Union (EMU), according
to a CBI survey published here today.
</P>
<P>
Seventy-two of the firms questioned said the UK should plan to
join EMU as soon as economic convergence is in place, while 16
percent disagreed.
</P>
<P>
When asked if their business would be prepared for the
potential impact of EMU if most of Europe moves ahead in 1999,
68 percent said yes, and 13 percent said no.
</P>
<P>
The CBI 1997 Member Survey was conducted to coincide with its
three-day National Conference which opens here today.
</P>
<P>
The Survey also shows that business believes better primary and
secondary education are key to the improving of their ability to
compete as the world enters the next century.
</P>
<P>
Business also prefers any additional spending on publicly
financed services to be funded through specific charges rather
than higher general taxation.
</P>
<P>
And the survey sends a clear message that business understands
the need to respond to the challenge of world climate change.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the survey, Colin Marshall, CBI President said at
a press conference: "The response of EMU gives a clear message
from CBI members, following the Chancellor's statement to
Parliament. A large majority want the Uk to join EMU provided the
conditions for success are in place.". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
