<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-09 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Movement Formed in Israel to Lobby Withdrawal from </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 9 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Labor Party MP Yossi
Beilin announced in Tel Aviv today that a movement was formed to
lobby the withdrawal of Israeli Defense Forces (IDF) from
Lebanon, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The movement includes politicians, artists and other
representatives from the grassroot units of the whole country,
Beilin told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The formation of this body is to continue persuading the IDF
to pull out from Lebanon, he added.
</P>
<P>
For the IDF withdrawal, he announced a nine-point program
which could be the alternatives to the Israeli military measures
in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The alternatives include carring out IDF's unilateral
withdrawal from Lebanon over a six-month period, seeking an
arrangement to ensure the safety of the South Lebanese Army
soldiers, improving the defense and security arrangements for the
Israeli soldiers and local residents along the northern border,
and seeking security arrangement with the Lebanese government.
</P>
<P>
The program would give Israel a greater chance to safeguard
its security and people in the north and reduce the losses of
lives of the IDF soldiers in South Lebanon, he said.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a security zone in South Lebanon in 1985 with
an area of about 1,100 square kilometers. Since then, the IDF
have been facing strong resistance from the Lebanese army,
particularly from the Hezbollah (Party of God).
</P>
<P>
Since January this year, about 40 IDF officers and soldiers
have lost their lives there, which caused a heated debate in
Israel on whether the IDF should be pulled out from Lebanon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
