<HEADLINE> UK Business Offeres Chance to Back World Cup Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BIRMINGHAM, November 9 (Xinhua) - British companies are being
offered an opportunity to back England's bid to host the World Cup
in 2006 at this week's CBI (Confederation of British Industry)
national conference.
</P>
<P>
1996 World Cup hero, Geoff Hurst MBE, will join the 2006
Campaign to set out to the companies present the shared value of
business backing for the bid, The Football Association announced
here today.
</P>
<P>
No more than 10 companies will be given the opportunity to
become corporate sponsors, giving them sponsorship of the bid
until the final decision in June 2000.
</P>
<P>
They will also be able to use the England 2006 logo on
literature and packaging and their name will appear on most
England 2006 materials, the FA said.
</P>
<P>
Support from British business for the Campaign will add
credibility and strength as well as giving the bid a stamp of
"British excellence". the Campaign will also seek expert advice
and support from the sponsors and get them involved in exporting
the bid internationally.
</P>
<P>
Other companies can associate with the bid by becoming
corporate friends. These companies will be encouraged to work with
the Foreign Office and local embassies to drive up recognition and
knowledge of the bid abroad.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the Campaign, its Director Alec Mcgivan said: "The
economic benefits to the whole country of staging the World Cup
will be enormous."
</P>
<P>
"Business will get the opportunity to be part of a dynamic
campaign around our most popular sport and the FA will profit from
their expertise and international contacts," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
