<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Holds Ceremonies to Mourn Victims of Nazi Pogrom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 9 (Xinhua) -- Germany today held a number of
ceremonies to mark the 59th anniversary of the so-called "Crystal
Night" of November 9, 1938 at which the German Nazis started mass
atrocities against Jews.
</P>
<P>
At the night of November 9, 1938, German Nazi supporters
launched the pogrom against Jews by torching numerous Jewish
synagogues and looting Jewish shops across the country.
</P>
<P>
Up to 30,000 German Jews were arrested and 91 of them were
killed at the night which heralded the mass killings of millions
of Jews later under the Nazi regime.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a ceremony in a former Nazi concentration camp at
Sachsenhausen near Berlin, leader of the German Jewish community,
Ignatz Bubis, today called for a serious analysis of the problem
of right extremism and warned against playing down the harm of the
Nazi violence.
</P>
<P>
A Jewish museum was reopened today at the former concentration
camp after restorations had been completed at two of the camp's
war-time barracks which were destroyed by German neo-Nazis during
an arson attack five years ago.
</P>
<P>
At the eastern German city of Leipzig, Mayor Hinrich
Lehmann-Grube said at a wreath-laying ceremony that only those who
kept alive the memories of the past were well prepared for the
future.
</P>
<P>
In another eastern German city Erfurt, some 300 demonstrators
marched to a local synagogue where they stood in silence for a
minute to mourn the victims of Nazi persecutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
