<HEADLINE> Iran Condemns US Sanctions against Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 9 (Xinhua) -- Iran today condemned the
economic sanctions by the United States against Sudan and itself,
saying that they were doomed to failure, the official news agency
IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
The American plots, stemming from its hostility to Muslims,
violated international norms and principles, Iran's Foreign
Ministry spokesman Mahmmud Mohammadi told reporters in Saudi
capital Riyadh, where he was accompanying Iranian Foreign Minister
Kamal Kharrazi on a visit.
</P>
<P>
The reasons for U.S. sanctions against Sudan were "totally
baseless and unfounded," he was quoted by the agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. announced last Tuesday that it decided to impose
economic sanctions against Sudan, which included freezing Sudanese
assests in the U.S., barring U.S. investment in Sudan and bans on
U.S. bank loans to Sudan and doing business with it.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. based the sanctions on Sudan's alleged support for
international terrorism, its attempts to disrupt stability in
neighboring countries, and its human rights records.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi said that Iran's solidarity with Muslim Sudan was in
line with its independent policies and refusal to bow to the world
power's pressures.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian spokesman attacked U.S. Undersecretary of State for
Trade Stuart Eizenstat for his threat to punish foreign companies
doing business with Iran, saying that it was a clear example of
U.S. intervention in the internal affairs of other countries.
</P>
<P>
He said that U.S. "monopolistic and selective policies" against
Iran were doomed to failure.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. decided last year that it would punish foreign
companies if they invested more than 20 million U.S. dollars in
Iran's oil and gas sectors.
</P>
<P>
However, French, Russian and Malaysian companies rejected the
U.S. decision, and announced to cooperate with Iran in the South
Pars Gas Deal of 2 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
