<HEADLINE> Report: Israel Delegates to Doha Receive Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 9 (Xinhua) -- Israeli delegates to next
week's Middle East and North Africa (MENA) economic conference
have received strict security guidelines on the threats of
attacks during their stay in Qatar, Israel Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted an Israeli security source as saying that
specific threats have been received that attacks would be
attempted at the conference, in particular on the Israelis
attending the gathering.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli delegation is still expected to be headed by
Foreign Minister David Levy despite his statement that he is
reconsidering the issue.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Trade and Industry Minister Natan Sharansky is also
to make the trip along with 30 public sector officials and 30 to
35 businessmen from private companies.
</P>
<P>
The source noted that the terror organization Abu Nidal had
announced that it would take actions against the conference,
which is scheduled to be held in the Qatari capital of Doha on
November 16-18.
</P>
<P>
The source said that the security arrangement for the
conference was not perfect, saying that the event is to take
place at the Sheraton Hotel in Doha, but because of the shortage
of guest rooms, most of the participants are to be hosted on three
large marinas docked at the nearby port.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the number of participants in the
conference could be between 1,800 and 3,000. However, the
unstable Arab-Israeli relations would contribute to the
uncertainty over the final number.
</P>
<P>
Four Arab countries -- Jordan, Oman, Yemen and Kuwait --
have confirmed their participation in the conference. And
United States Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and
Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy will also attend the
meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
