<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Staying Out EMU Poses Serious Costs to UK: Economists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BIRMINGHAM, November 9 (Xinhua) - Staying out of the single
currency poses serious long term and short term costs, according
to a group of economists surveyed by the European movement.
</P>
<P>
A majority of them believe that the costs will include
exclusion from economic decision making and loss of inward
investment.
</P>
<P>
The balance of opinion within the panel is that the British
economic cycle is currently too out of line with other EU
economies to be able to join in the first wave.
</P>
<P>
However, a majority of the panel believes the cycles will come
gradually into line over the next two years, enabling British
membership of EMU shortly afterwards.
</P>
<P>
There is a consensus that EMU will go ahead on 1 January 1999,
and that membership will be broad, with most estimates being that
EMU will include ten or eleven.
</P>
<P>
The only definite "out" countries identified by the economists
are Britain, Greece, Denmark and Sweden.
</P>
<P>
The European Movement's Economists Panel is made up of eleven
senior economists from a variety of backgrounds and with a range
of views on EMU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
