<HEADLINE> Berger: U-2 Expected to Resume Flights Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 9 (Xinhua) -- U.S. National Security
Adviser Sandy Berger said on Sunday that American U-2 planes
were expected to resume flights over Iraq for U.N. inspections
missions.
</P>
<P>
"It would be my expectation" to resume on Monday the flights of
U-2 planes over Iraq, Berger told a CNN interview.
</P>
<P>
The U-2 flights were scheduled last week, but were postponed as
a U.N. three-man mission was in Baghdad to hold talks with Iraqi
officials in an effort to defuse impasse triggered by Iraq's
refusal to allow U.N. arms inspection teams that include Americans
to discharge their jobs.
</P>
<P>
Berger warned Iraq there would be "consequences" if it tries to
shoot down any of the planes.
</P>
<P>
"I would hope the Iraqis would not shoot at a plane on the U.N.
mission," he said. "It would not only be an attack on that plane,
it would be essentially an attack on the international
community... there will be consequences."
</P>
<P>
Berger also rejected Iraq's request that the United Nations
reduce the number of Americans in the inspection teams and replace
U-2 with non-American planes for the reconnaissance flights.
</P>
<P>
"This operation has proceeded for six years with great
professionalism," he said. "It is not for Saddam Hussein to
dictate who the inspectors are." 
</P>
