<HEADLINE> Saudi Leaders, Iranian Minister Discuss Bilateral </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, November 9 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabian leaders today
held meetings with visiting Iranian foreign minister on improving
the lukewarm bilateral relations, reports reaching here from Saudi
capital Riyadh said.
</P>
<P>
Kamal Kharrazi, who arrived here Saturday, also delivered
letters from Iranian President Mohammad Khatami to Saudi King Fahd
Ibn Abdul-Aziz and Crown Prince and Deputy Prime Minister Abdullah
Ibn Abdul-Aziz during the meetings.
</P>
<P>
The letters focus on bilateral relations, Saudi Press Agency
said, but without disclosing details of the letters.
</P>
<P>
The news agency quoted Kharrazi as assuring Abdullah of "Iran's
commitment to improving relations with Saudi Arabia and opening a
new page based on good neighborliness and promotion of common
interests."
</P>
<P>
He also said Iran is willing to forge good and strong ties with
the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) states and keen on opening a
new page of cooperation and protection of mutual interests.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi would meet his Saudi counterpart Saud Al-Faisal Monday
to discuss bilateral, regional and Iran-GCC relations.
</P>
<P>
Then he will leave for Kuwait to continue his GCC visit, which
will also bring him to the United Arab Emirates, Oman, Qatar and
Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Iran and its Gulf Arab neighbors have been
warming up since the start of this year after nearly two decades
of strained ties which were resulted from the presence of Western
forces in the Gulf, Tehran's arms strengthening program and the
ramifications of Iran's Islamic revolution launched in 1979 as
well as territorial disputes.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats in Saudi Arabia were quoted as saying Kharrazi's Gulf
tour is a new sign of a thaw in ties between Iran and the GCC
states. 
</P>
