<HEADLINE> Egypt: Peace Process Reaches Stage of Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 9 (Xinhua) -- Egypt warned today that the
Mideast peace process has reached the stage of political crisis
because of current intransigent policies of the Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa, at the monthly forum of the
Egyptian Tourism Companies Chambers Federation this evening, said
he is not optimistic about reaching a solution in the near future.
</P>
<P>
On the Doha Arab-Israeli economic conference scheduled for
16-18 this month in the Qatari capital, Moussa said it comes at a
time the peace process "has never been so crippled" over the past
two years.
</P>
<P>
Moussa voiced astonishment at the logic that it is possible to
go on with economic cooperation and defer political issues till
later. "This is warped logic," he said.
</P>
<P>
Arab presence at the Doha conference will be very limited,
Moussa said, adding that very few Arab countries have agreed to
participate.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the annual regional economic gathering is being
used as a political cover for "other non-economic matters."
</P>
<P>
"Economic gatherings are supposed to provide a chance for
businesspeople to meet. But the fact is that ever since the
regional economic conference was held in Casablanca (Morocco, in
1994), it has been tinged with politics," he said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has since been fighting such politicization attempts,
Moussa said, adding that Egypt's hosting of the economic
conference last year took place on the understanding that it was
no summit meeting but an economic event.
</P>
<P>
The fourth Middle East and North Africa economic conference has
divided the Arab world due to Israel's participation. Most Arab
countries are lukewarm to the gathering when the peace process has
been on ice for eight months.
</P>
<P>
Cairo has criticized the conference, the fourth since its
initiation in 1994 as a spinoff of the Mideast peace process, but
decided to reserve its own decision until the last moment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
