<HEADLINE> Kuwait Says No Change in its Mideast Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait said today that its
decision to attend the controversial Middle East and North Africa
(MENA) economic conference does not mean a change in its Middle
East policy.
</P>
<P>
Attending the conference along with Israel does not mean to
establish any kind of relations with the Jewish state, Kuwaiti State
Minister for Cabinet Affairs Abdul Aziz Dakhil Al-Dakhil said at a
press briefing.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait announced Sunday that it would send an under-secretary
of the Finance Ministry to the MENA conference, which Israel would
also attend, due to be held on November 16-18 in Qatari capital
Doha.
</P>
<P>
Al-Dakhil stressed that Kuwait had set concert progress in the
Middle East peace process as a necessary condition for normalizing
its relations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait does not have economic ties with Israel and has halted
its normalization process with the Jewish state following Israel's
Jewish settlement construction in Arab East Jerusalem last March.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Chamber of Commerce and Industry has said it would not
participate in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The MENA conference was initially aimed at promoting economic
cooperation between the Arab world and Israel along with the
progress in the peace process. The previous three MENA gatherings
were held in Morocco, Jordan and Egypt from 1994 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
But due to Israel's hard-line policies blocking the peace
process, some Arab countries, including Syria and Lebanon, have
declared to boycott the Doha conference, and Egypt is waiting to
see if there is any headway in the Palestinian-Israeli talks and
will make clear its attitude at the last minute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
