<HEADLINE> Nordic Countries Divide on Baltic Countries' EU Entry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Prime ministers of five
Nordic countries continue to hold different views on the entry
into the European Union (EU) by three Baltic countries, namely,
Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania.
</P>
<P>
Five prime ministers from Finland, Sweden, Denmark, Norway and
Iceland, who met here today to discuss European integration, entry
into European Economic and Monetary Union (EMU) and the Schengen
Accord, voiced at a press conference their disagreement over
admitting the Baltic states into the EU.
</P>
<P>
Finish Prime Minister Paavo Lipponen said Finland favored the
suggestion by the Commission of the European Union of including
Estonia into the group of countries for the next round of
negotiations on EU enlargement.
</P>
<P>
Demark and Sweden, however, hoped the negotiation would also
include Latvia and Lithuania.
</P>
<P>
Denmark Prime Minister Poul Rasmussen said the entry issue
should be decided by politicians instead of the Commission of
European Union.
</P>
<P>
Swedish Prime Minister Goran Persson insisted on Latvia and
Lithuania's participation in the negotiations, viewing it as an
important political signal.
</P>
<P>
The Nordic prime ministers will also hold talks with prime
ministers from the three Baltic countries, which will mainly focus
on the cooperation between North European and Baltic countries, EU
integration and regional security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
