<HEADLINE> Beijing Hosts '97 International Gingko Seminar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The '97 International Gingko
Seminar opened today in Beijing under the joint sponsorship of the
State Science and Technology Commission, the Beaufour Ipsen Group
from France and Schwabe Corp from Germany, two major international
pharmaceutical manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
More than 150 scientists from gingko research institutions and
pharmaceutical enterprises from France, Germany, the United
States, Switzerland, the Netherlands, Japan and China are
attending the three-day seminar.
</P>
<P>
The event is the world's first large-scale international
seminar on the comprehensive development of gingko. Participants
will discuss the latest developments related to plant propagation,
techniques for processing leaves, research on application of
gingko pharmaceuticals and trends in the gingko pharmaceutical
industry.
</P>
<P>
Participants will also exhibit new production technology and
new products.
</P>
<P>
The gingko tree, or the "longevity tree", is a specialized
plant species which survived the glacial period.
</P>
<P>
Gingko pharmaceuticals are used for the prevention and
treatment of cardiovascular diseases, senile dementia and organic
neurosis.
</P>
<P>
Clinic research currently focuses on the application of gingko
pharmaceuticals for the treatment of respiratory tract allergies,
the formation of thrombus and rejections of human organ
transplants.
</P>
<P>
The current annual sales volume for gingko products exceeds two
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The species originated in China and the country has currently
over 70 percent of the world's gingko trees. The annual output of
gingko fruit and leaves in China stands at 12,000 tons and 15,000
tons respectively. China's output of gingko extracts approaches
one million tons annually.
</P>
<P>
Chinese research institutions and enterprises are jointly
producing gingko leave tablets and capsules. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
