<HEADLINE> U.S. Civil Rights Nomination in Jeopardy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The Judiciary Committee of
the U.S. Senate will consider, and probably kill, the nomination
of Bill Lann Lee to head the Justice Department's Civil Rights
Division this week, the committee chairman says.
</P>
<P>
Senator Orrin Hatch, a Republican, rejected on Sunday a request
by Democrats on the committee for another hearing to let Lee
answer charges that he has been an advocate of racial and gender
preferences.
</P>
<P>
"An additional hearing won't add a thing, and we are not going
to have an additional hearing. We'll just go to a vote and let the
chips fall whichever way they may," Hatch said on CBS' "Face the
Nation." The vote was set for Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Democrats on the Judiciary Committee last week sought the
further hearing and postponement of the vote on Lee when it became
apparent it would turn out 9-9. Tie votes count as a rejection.
</P>
<P>
"As far as right now this nomination is dead," Hatch said.
</P>
<P>
In his current position as Western regional counsel for the
NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund, based in Los Angeles,
Lee has opposed California state efforts to end affirmative action
programs for schools and jobs.
</P>
<P>
Hatch called Lee a "very nice person" but said "this man has
pushed preferential rights and special treatment throughout his
life."
</P>
<P>
"It's not about Bill Lann Lee, it's about the positions he's
advocated," Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott said on "Fox News
Sunday."
</P>
<P>
Senator Patrick Leahy, a ranking Democrat on the Judiciary
Committee, accused Republicans of using Lee for political
purposes.
</P>
<P>
"Republican leaders want to kill this nomination as a trophy,"
he said. "They are out to please extremists in their party who
oppose relief when equal opportunity is denied to women or
minorities in the workplace." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
