<DOCNO> XIE19971110.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Canadians Want Action on Climate Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, November 10 (Xinhua) -- A majority of Canadians want
the government to act on climate change even if it slows the
economy, a new poll suggested.
</P>
<P>
The survey is part of a massive international poll of
environmental attitudes in 24 countries. It found support in 15 of
the countries, including Canada, for concerted action on climate
change, said a report today.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-one Canadians agreed that "we should assume the worst and
take major action now to reduce human impacts on climate even if
there are major costs," the poll showed.
</P>
<P>
Yet, 32 percent of the 1,530 Canadians surveyed said no major
action should be taken until more is known about the science.
</P>
<P>
Scientists say growing atmospheric levels of carbon dioxide and
other greenhouse gases are warming the earth's surface, which
would lead to disastrous consequences.
</P>
<P>
The poll indicated that "Canadians are very confused about the
science of climate change, but in the face of scientific
uncertainty, their leaders should err on the side of environmental
caution," said Doug Miller, head of Environics International Ltd.,
which conducted the survey.
</P>
<P>
The survey found public support for immediate action on climate
change was highest in France (74 percent), Germany (71 percent),
Italy (71 percent), Switzerland (70 percent), Japan (69 percent),
Australia (67 percent), New Zealand (65 percent) and Canada (61
percent).
</P>
<P>
The Americans were evenly divided between those who want
immediate action and those who believe major action should be
shelved until the science is better understood.
</P>
<P>
The poll results are considered accurate within 2.5 percentage
points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971110.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Prepares For EMU Membership: Brown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BIRMINGHAM, November 10 (Xinhua) - British Chancellor of the
Exchequer Gordon Brown announced today his country's first
practical steps in preparation for joining the European Economic
and Monetary Union (EMU).
</P>
<P>
The chancellor said that ministers are planning a public
education exercise to familiarize British people with the use of
euro notes and coins early in the next century.
</P>
<P>
Brown made the announcement in his speech at the National
Conference of the Confederation of British Industry (CBI).
</P>
<P>
The British government will take all steps necessary to
encourage the use of the euro when the single European currency is
introduced on January 1, 1999, said the Chancellor.
</P>
<P>
"We will play our part in shaping (EMU) so that if we wish, we
can join the single currency early in the next parliament," he
said. The current parliament expires in 2002.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that the chancellor is trying to cement
the Labor government's growing links with business by delivering
what is seen as the most pro-EMU speech.
</P>
<P>
Brown also said business circles and government will work
together to prepare Britain for the monetary union. The CBI will
play a "crucial role" in the practical preparation work, he said.
</P>
<P>
"I believe there is a growing consensus for the principle of a
single currency. These preparations are not cosmetic but real,"
the Chancellor said.
</P>
<P>
He also told the conference that from the launch of the euro,
British companies will be able to file company accounts, issue
shares, have bank accounts and pay taxes all in the euro
currency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
