<HEADLINE> Canadian FM Calls for Caution in Iraqi Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Canadian Foreign
Minister Lloyd Axworthy today urged the U.S. and Iraq to take
caution in handling the crisis caused by Baghdad's decision to
expel Americans in the U.N. weapons inspection teams in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Following a meeting with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak,
Axworthy told reporters that they held the same view that the
development in Iraq should be handled cautiously to avoid further
escalation.
</P>
<P>
He said Iraq should comply with U.N. Security Council
resolutions while expressing the hope that the U.S. should take
the matter to the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
When asked about a possible U.S. strike against Iraq without
referring to the Council, the Canadian foreign minister said the
situation is different this time because the crisis over weapons
inspection teams is a "pure U.N. affair."
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa, who also attended the
meeting, expressed the hope that the crisis can be resolved
diplomatically and that the Security Council puts an end to it
through a constructive solution between the U.N. Special
Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of eliminating Iraqi weapons of mass
destruction and the Iraqi government.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has barred U.N. weapon inspection teams that included
Americans for a seventh day and threatened to shoot down an
American U-2 surveillance plane that resumed flights over Iraq
today as part of U.N. monitoring operations in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
While the United States has insisted that there will be no
negotiations with Iraq on the issue of inspections, and
U.S. President Bill Clinton reiterated Sunday that the United
States would not tolerate any attempt to attack the U-2 flights.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has charged that the American inspectors are spies trying
to prolong the U.N. sanctions imposed after the 1990 Iraqi
invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Axworthy, who arrived here Sunday, will also visit Israel, the
Palestinian self-rule areas, Syria, Lebanon and Jordan to
highlight Canada's interest to help break the present standstill
plaguing the Arab-Israeli peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
