<HEADLINE> Nordic Stocks: Bears Not Ready for Hibernation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, November 10 (Xinhua)-- Nordic stocks are seen
extending Friday's losses in the week ahead amid concern that
turbulence in Asian markets will hurt earnings for exporters such
as forestry companies and ABB, the Swedish-Swiss engineering
company, according to press here today.
</P>
<P>
"We are now putting a question mark on next year's earnings
outlook because of the Asian turmoil and also weaker growth
outlook," said Bjoern Germer, head of equities at Matteus
Fondkommission. "The trend is now downwards and engineering,
forestry and steel companies are most battered."
</P>
<P>
Nordic forestry firms were among the biggest decliners in the
week. Sweden's "Stora" fell 4.8 percent while Finland's "Enso"
slumped 4.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Nokia, the Finnish telecommunications equipment maker which
makes up 40 percent of Finland's benchmark index, fell 4.2 percent
Friday. Nokia generates about one-fifth of its sales in Asia, as
does Sweden's Ericsson.
</P>
<P>
Blue-chips like Norsk Hydro and Petroleum Geo-Services led the
Norwegian losses. Similarly, Kvaerner, a Norwegian construction
and shipbuilding firm with one-quarter of its sales in Asia, fell
1.4 kroner on Friday. 
</P>
