<HEADLINE> China's Largest State-Owned Enterprise Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The Qilu Petrochemical Company,
a subsidiary of the China National Petrochemical Corp., has
completed the last round of legal procedures for mergering two
state-owned chemical plants which have combined debts of 3.6
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The merger, the first involving state-owned enterprises,
involves the largest amount of funds, according to Vice-Premier Wu
Bangguo. Wu attended the signing ceremony held today in the city
of Zibo, in east China's Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
The merger involves the Zibo Chemical Fiber Plant and the Zibo
Petrochemical Plant which have total assests of some 1.6 billion
yuan, but which also have an assets-to-liability ratio of 233
percent.
</P>
<P>
The merger is expected to introduce two billion yuan in assets
into circulation.
</P>
<P>
The Qilu Petrochemical Co. is currently in the process of
raising its annual ethylene production capacity from 300,000 tons
to 450,000 tons, and expects to substantially increase its
comprehensive economic returns as a result of the
expansion. 
</P>
