<HEADLINE> Canada's Ontario Teachers End Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Teachers in Canada's largest
province of Ontario returned to work today, marking the end of the
biggest strike by teachers in Canadian history.
</P>
<P>
The two-week strike officially ended Sunday afternoon, after the
high school teachers' union said its members would join elementary
school teachers in returning to work today.
</P>
<P>
The unions said the strike had drawn public and media attention
to the provincial government's reform legislation and it is time now
to protest in other ways.
</P>
<P>
The legislation, still under discussion, would allow the
government to cut one billion dollars (710 million U.S. dollars)
from the education system and layoff 10,000 teachers, the unions
said.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the government said that the reforms are intended to
improve the efficiency of the education system. 
