<HEADLINE> Germany Opposes New EU Spendings on Job Creation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Bonn would oppose any European
Union project to boost state spendings on job creation at the
upcoming EU job summit in Luxembourg on November 20-21, German
officials indicated here today.
</P>
<P>
Wolfgang Schaeuble, a senior aide to German Chancellor Helmut
Kohl, said at an expert panel on employment today in Bonn that
more state spendings on job creation would not help cut the EU
record unemployment of 18 million, but would instead make things
worse.
</P>
<P>
He also rejected the idea of imposing higher job creation
targets on EU states.
</P>
<P>
Instead of more coordinated intervention from Brussels, EU
states should take more decentralized approach to job creation, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The German central bank, known as the Bundesbank, as well as
the Federal Labour Office today also stressed at the panel
discussions that job creation should be the responsibility of
individual EU states.
</P>
<P>
Kohl is due to make clear Germany's position on the EU
employment summit in a speech to the parliament on Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
