<DOCNO> XIE19971110.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mogadishu Hard Hit by Lack of Petrol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, November 10 (Xinhua)-- The economical status of the
Somali capital is still facing hardships due to lack of petrol
despite the end of the strong southeast winds of the Monsoon
early in the month.
</P>
<P>
Several commercial vessels and boats carrying miscellaneous
food items and other commodities from the Gulf countries are
moored at the natural ports of EI-Ma'an and Merca town controlled
by Ali Mahdi and Hussein Aidid respectively.
</P>
<P>
As the food prices remain stable in the main markets of the
capital, Mogadishu is facing its harshest fuel shortage for many
years.
</P>
<P>
The fuel prices in Mogadishu has tripled today, especially the
petrol. Each liter of petrol which was valued at 0.30 U.S. Dollar
three days ago is today sold on 7,000 Somali Shillings, nearly
one U.S. Dollar.
</P>
<P>
Administration officer of one of Mogadishu fuel importing
enterprises SOPICO Hussein Mohamud Omar said their petrol
reservoirs are almost empty. "this is what causes the prices to
rise," he said, "but we're expecting more fuel to arrive within a
few days."
</P>
<P>
According to Mr. Omar, they imported the fuel from the Gulf
countries, mainly from the United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the high prices is also attributed to the
strengthened sanctions imposed on Iraq by the United nations
where cheap fuel was leaked out from smuggling tankers.
</P>
<P>
The streets of the Somali capital today are deserted by the
public transport which uses petrol.
</P>
<P>
All mini-buses have stopped operating, but large diesel
vehicles are seen circulating in the rain-flooded streets of
Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
People walk one after another in the streets leading to and
from the green lines that divide Mogadishu owing to the fuel
shortage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971110.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 14:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Opposition Leader Rejects Netanyahu's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Israeli opposition Labor
party leader Ehud Barak today rejected the call from Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu for national reconciliation,
according to Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Barak was reacting to the statements Netanyahu made overnight
at the Likud party Convention in Jerusalem. In an unprecedented
move, Netanyahu openly acknowledge the Labor's contribution to the
country's security and historic achievements.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, who opened the convention with one-minute silence
to mark the second anniversary of the assassination of former
Labor premier Yitzhak Rabin, called for national unity, saying
he was extending out his "hand of peace and conciliation to all
parts of this nation."
</P>
<P>
Barak was quoted by Israel Radio as responding that there is a
gap between Netanyahu's statements and deeds. He added that the
real opportunity for Netanyahu to do so is for him to offer an
apology, at the Knesset (Parliament) memorial ceremony Tuesday
held for Rabin, for his incitement that preceded Rabin's
killing.
</P>
<P>
Rabin was shot dead on November 4, 1995, at a Tel Aviv peace
rally by a radical Jew named Yigal Amir, who claimed he killed
Rabin in order to prevent him from handing over more Israeli
land to Arabs.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is widely blamed for partially responsible for
organizing the inciting campaign against Rabin and his government
over his peace policies. The Labor party is demanding Netanyahu
make a formal apology for the incitement campaign.
</P>
<P>
At the biggest ever peace rally in the country's history held
in Tel Aviv Saturday night, about 200,000 people gathered at the
Rabin Square, where Rabin was murdered, to show their support for
peace and demand Netanyahu apologize for his role in the Rabin
affair.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the rally, Barak vowed to carry on Rabin's peace
legacy and strive to replace the Netanyahu government "with a
responsible leadership."
</P>
<P>
Another opposition leader Yossi Sarid, head of Meretz party,
directly called for Netanyahu's resignation to take
responsibility for one of the biggest tragedies the Jewish state
has experienced.
</P>
<P>
The ruling and opposition parties are expected to trade slurs
at the Knesset ceremony to mark Rabin's assassination. Today, a
group of Labor Knesset members laid wraths at Rabin's graveside
on Mourt Herzl, western Jerusalem, to pay their tributes to the
pioneering peacemaker. 
</P>
</TEXT>
