<HEADLINE> HK Welcomes Business From World: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) welcomes business from all parts of
the world and continues to practice a free trade and open market
economic policy, a senior official of the SAR said today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the one-day Hong Kong, Shanghai, Osaka (Japan)
Economic Cooperation Conference held at the Hong Kong Convention
and Exhibition Center, Secretary for Trade and Industry Denise Yue
stressed that the Basic Law protects investment here.
</P>
<P>
She said that after its return to the motherland on July 1,
Hong Kong has "continued to practice a free trade and open market
economic policy." "We welcome business from all parts of the world
to come to Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
"As an open economy, we have no special approval procedure for
foreign investments. We impose no conditions for admission. And we
do not interfere with management of investments in Hong Kong. We
also put no roadblocks before investment overseas by our own
entrepreneurs or by others who wish to invest in other places
through Hong Kong," Yue stated.
</P>
<P>
She stressed that the SAR believes that the best way to attract
and protect investment is to institute an investment regime that
is free, open, transparent and stable.
</P>
<P>
These principles are firmly enshrined in the Basic Law, Yue
said, noting that the Basic Law, which has delineated and
institutionalized the unprecedented concept of "one country, two
systems," protects the rights, freedoms and lifestyle of the SAR
people.
</P>
<P>
At the same meeting, SAR Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa
reiterated earlier that Hong Kong's currency must be and will be
linked with the U.S. dollar and there is absolutely no need for
Hong Kong to change the peg.  
</P>
</TEXT>
