<HEADLINE> Chinese Banyan Crowned "King" of HK Urban Trees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 10 (Xinhua) -- A 200-year-old Chinese
Banyan in Kowloon Park has been crowned "King" of Hong Kong urban
trees as a result of a three-month competition, the Provisional
Urban Council of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
announced today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a rare Rain Tree at Wong Chuk Hang Road in Southern
District, Hong Kong, was elected as the "Most Popular Urban Tree,"
the council said.
</P>
<P>
Both trees were selected from 370 trees in the urban area of
Hong Kong nominated by the public in May and June. The nominations
were shortlisted into nine finalist trees representing each urban
district. The "King" of urban trees was selected by a jury panel
comprising tree experts and environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
The "King" of Hong Kong Urban Trees Competition was designed to
promote public understanding of the importance of preservation of
urban trees, according to a spokesman for the council.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Banyan is the largest specimen with the thickest
trunk (4.3 meters in width) in urban Hong Kong. It is 18 meters
tall and has a crown spread of 27 meters wide. The rare Rain Tree
has an enormous height of 22 meters and a crown spread of 38
meters wide. Its huge dome-like canopy can be appreciated by road
users and residents in a large hinterland area.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
