<HEADLINE> Cyprus Welcomes U.S. Envoy's visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government today
welcomed a forthcoming visit to the island by the
U.S. Presidential Emissary for Cyprus and said it expects positive
results.
</P>
<P>
Richard Holbrooke, who brokered the Bosnian peace deal, is
coming to Cyprus later today for meetings with the leaders of the
two communities, including a joint meeting which will be held
Tuesday, Government Spokesman Manolis Christofides said at his
daily press briefing here today.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after his arrival, Holbrooke will have a meeting
with President Glafcos Clerides and will then cross into northern
part of the island for a meeting with Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Christofides welcomed international interest, especially on
behalf of the U.S., in a settlement to the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
"It is the first time there is so much international interest,
on behalf of the U.S., the U.N., the European Union and many
others," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman added the "American interest in a settlement is
expressed at the highest possible level, from President (Bill)
Clinton to the Secretary of State and other officials."
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that Turkish intransigence would be
overcome and a settlement to the protracted Cyprus question would
be achieved.
</P>
<P>
Thomas Miller, U.S. State Department Special Coordinator for
Cyprus, arrived here Monday night to make preparations for
Holbrooke's discussions on the island.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a meeting with Clerides this morning, Miller
said he is trying to "make progress" toward a Cyprus settlement.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Holbrooke comes to Cyprus to hold discussions,
not negotiations with the Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides.
</P>
<P>
Miller, however, declined to make any optimistic predictions
on the results of Holbrooke's first visit to the island.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unresolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkish troops invaded and took over the
northern third part in the wake of a short-lived Greek Cypriot coup in
Nicosia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
