<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Favors More Funds for Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 10 (Xinhua) -- A WHO official said today
Africa needs more than double its annual budget allocation of 76
million U.S. Dollars for effective disease control and
implementation of other health programs in the poorest continent.
</P>
<P>
Regional director of the World Health Organization (WHO) for
Africa Ebrahim Samba said here that the ever-growing poverty
militated against efforts by both WHO and other health
organizations trying to improve the state of health in the
continent.
</P>
<P>
"For instance, this year all of Africa could be hit by a
severe drought that will inevitably multiply the malnutrition
rate and open the way for the spread of diseases," said Samba.
</P>
<P>
He said the spread of AIDS is on the increase in southern and
central Africa where experts estimated the rate of infection to
average 10 percent of national populations.
</P>
<P>
As a result life expectancy is already being estimated to drop
from 50 years at present to 40 years by the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
However, Samba paid tribute to African leaders, who, through
the Organization of African Unity (OAU) made an undertaking to
fight diseases by allocating more funds to the health sector.
</P>
<P>
"In 1995, OAU resolved to fight for the eradication of AIDS
and although the disease is still ravaging economies, the effort
against it is noticeable at national and continental levels," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the OAU resolution in 1996 to fight polio had
also received tremendous support from governments and "I am happy
to say very very soon polio will be eradicated in Africa."
</P>
<P>
"However, malaria is still a problem, hence the declaration in
June in Harare, by OAU heads of state to allocate more resources
to programs against its spread," said Samba. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
