<HEADLINE> Mubarak Pays Lightning Visit to Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
left here for Riyadh today for coordination with Saudi leaders on
the controversial economic conference to be held in Qatar later
this month.
</P>
<P>
During his brief visit, Mubarak is expected to meet with King
Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz and Crown Prince Abdallah Ibn Abdul-Aziz on
the Mideast peace developments, bilateral ties, the outcome of his
recent tour of the United Arab Emirates (UAE), Oman and Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
The president has said that he did not discuss with leaders of
the UAE, Oman and Bahrain the topic of the forthcoming Middle East
and North Africa (MENA) Economic Conference, scheduled for
November 16-18 in Qatari capital Doha.
</P>
<P>
"I've preferred to let the matter be decided on by every
country in accordance with its interests," said the president.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt will take an appropriate decision (on whether go to the
conference) at the opportune time," he added, noting that any
Egyptian stance on that score will spring from the view of how far
the gathering will benefit the region that is bogged down in a
peace stalemate.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said on November 1 that Israel's failure to honor peace
pledges rendered the MENA conference meaningless.
</P>
<P>
Some Arab states, including Saudi Arabia and the UAE, have said
they would boycott the controversial meeting.
</P>
<P>
The annual gathering, initiated in 1994 as a spinoff of the
Mideast peace process, was designed to integrate Israel into the
regional economy. 
</P>
