<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liberalization, Globalization Not One-way Street-Gujral </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 10 (Xinhua)-- Indian Prime Minister Inder
Kumar Gujral said today that liberalization and globalization
cannot be a one-way street.
</P>
<P>
Opening a two-day meeting of the Council of the Socialist
International here, Gujral said that for both these processes to
be sustainable, they must be based on a genuine appreciation of
different points of view and different objective conditions.
</P>
<P>
"If, to the developed countries, globalization is a means to
optimize profits by locating factories near the areas of
consumption or a way to overcome high labor costs and escape high
tariff barriers, it is equally important that to developing
countries this process means better terms of trade and market
access and a greater inflow of resources for critical
developmental needs," Gujral said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the recent exchange rate fluctuations across Asia,
Gujral termed it as a significant pointer to the need to insulate
the developing economies from the aggressive flow of global
finance. "It is only if these factors are kept in mind that global
change can take place on the resilient foundations of long-term
success," he said.
</P>
<P>
The 21st century must be a period when the issues arising out
of the process of globalization are systematically and equitably
dealt with and resolved, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
