<HEADLINE> Big Powers Asked to Mediate in U.N.-Iraq Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Big countries such as Russia,
Britain, France, China and Japan should offer their mediation and
help end the conflict between the United Nations and Iraq, an
Indonesian legislator said here today.
</P>
<P>
"Big countries other than the United States could see how Iraq
could improve its economy. And they could do so without (being
influenced) by U.S. interests stipulated in U.N. decisions,
particularly in the U.N. Security Council," deputy chairman of the
House Committee on Domestic and Foreign Affairs, Abu Hasan Sazili,
said.
</P>
<P>
Sazili expressed concern over the escalating U.N.-Iraq
conflict, with U.S. interests in the shadow.
</P>
<P>
He said the United Nations fears that a war might break out
following the war of words between the United States and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi President Saddam Hussein has threatened to shoot down any
U.S. plane carrying out reconnaissance mission for a U.N. special
committee.
</P>
<P>
In turn, the U.S. government has warned that shooting down any
U.S. plane would be a declaration of war.
</P>
<P>
The conflict was renewed after Iraq banned U.S. experts on a
U.N. team from inspecting its weapons sites, on the grounds that
Washington is using the U.N. Security Council to keep in place the
sanctions against it.
</P>
<P>
The conflict is expected to escalate further now that American
experts claimed that Iraq has been found developing chemical
weapons, Sazili said.
</P>
<P>
"If the conflict becomes an open war, it will damage all sides.
Thus, the world community should seek ways to establish a dialogue
between the United Nations and Iraq to settle the conflict
(peacefully)," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
