<HEADLINE> Australia Gets More International Passengers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The number of passengers on
airlines flying in and out of Australia in May this year increased
by 10.5 percent over a year ago, according to figures released by
the Transport Department today.
</P>
<P>
This continued the trend of monthly increases unbroken since
June 1991.
</P>
<P>
The 13.685 million passengers carried for the year ended May
1997 was an increase of 8.8 percent over the year ended May 1996,
the figures show.
</P>
<P>
The busiest 10 routes in May were: Auckland-Sydney, Los
Angeles-Sydney, Singapore-Sydney, Hong Kong-Sydney, Tokyo-Sydney,
Auckland-Brisbane, Singapore-Perth, Auckland-Melbourne,
Osaka-Sydney and Singapore-Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
Sydney Airport was the gateway for 49 percent of the passengers
while 16.5 percent went through Melbourne and 16.4 percent through
Brisbane.
</P>
<P>
Qantas carried 39.2 percent of Australia's international
passengers in May 1997, followed by Air New Zealand, Singapore
Airlines, JAL, United Airlines, Ansett, Malaysia Airlines, Cathay
Pacific and British Airways.  
</P>
</TEXT>
