<HEADLINE> Stocks Fall to Record Low for Year in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Tokyo stocks finished at a
record low for the year today on persistent selling in bank issues.
</P>
<P>
The key Nikkei average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange ended at 15,697 points, down
139.16 points, or 0.88 percent from last Friday's closing.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
issues on the First Section, declined 19.49 points or 1.58 percent
to 1,210.58 points.
</P>
<P>
Volume on the First Section came to an estimated 430 million
shares, down from Friday's 508.30 million shares.
</P>
<P>
On the Tokyo Foreign Exchange, the U.S. dollar hovered around
the 124 yen line amid a dearth of trading incentives, 124 yen line
for the first time since May.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. currency was adopted at 124.05-07 yen at 5 p.m., up
from 123.96-99 yen at 9 a.m. in Tokyo, but down from 124.20-30 yen
late Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
