<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Trial-supplying Power to Zimbabwe, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Cahora Bassa, Africa's most
powerful hydro-electric station based in Songo County in
Mozambique's northwestern Tete Province has been trial-supplying
power to Zimbabwe since last week.
</P>
<P>
Noticias, the local daily today quoted Goncalves Guedes,
director of the services department of the station as saying that
the trial-supply, which started Monday last week, will come to an
end early this week.
</P>
<P>
Guedes said, "everything is fine and the effect ideal."
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that 150 mwh would be supplied at the first
phase, and it plans to supply Zimbabwe with 500 mwh after the
final trial in late November and early December.
</P>
<P>
Earlier at the beginning of October, the station had
trial-supplied electricity through the power line extending some
1,000 km to South Africa, which is the first of its kind in 14
years.
</P>
<P>
Guedes said that they had tried to use the western line to
deliver 640-650 mwh to Zimbabwe last week, and will make a test
of the eastern line again this week, planning to trial deliver
electricity to South Africa in December.
</P>
<P>
The Cahora Bassa Hydro-electric Station, which started its
commercial operation in 1977, is claimed to be one of the largest
hydro-power stations in the world.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is in a position to buy three-quarters of the
total capacity of the giant 2,000 megawatt dam. Along with
Zimbabwe and South Africa, Malawi is also interested in getting
electricity from the huge dam.
</P>
<P>
Over 2,000 pylons had been destroyed during the Mozambican
civil war which ended in 1992. The entire job consisted of
putting up 2,200 pylons along the 900 km transmission line
running from Cahora Bassa in Mozambique's Tete Province to South
Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
