<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia, New Zealand Reach "Open Skies" Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and New Zealand
today reached an agreement on "open skies" air services, paving
the way for the full liberalization of such services between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, reached in Wellington after consultations
between Malaysian Transport Minister Ling Liong Sik and his New
Zealand counterpart Jenny Shipley, who is also prime
minister-designate, is expected to be signed later this year, Ling
said in a statement issued here.
</P>
<P>
He said the establishment of the open skies policy opened a new
phase in developing the aviation relationship between the two
countries which first signed an air services agreement in 1989.
</P>
<P>
"This is a reflection of the genuine desire of the governments
of Malaysia and New Zealand to liberalize and develop efficient,
viable and mutually beneficial international air services," Ling
said.
</P>
<P>
The main principles of the open skies agreement include
multiple designation of airlines and no limitation on the level of
frequencies that can be operated by designated airlines.
</P>
<P>
Ling said the new agreement will also facilitate further
development of trade, investment, tourism and people-to-people
contact between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
