<DOCNO> XIE19971110.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Botswana President to Step Down: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Botswana President
Ketumile Masire is expected to announce his retirement from
office today at the opening session of parliament, South African
Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
SAPA quoted sources within the Botswana National Assembly as
saying that Masire had ordered an unusual number of personal
invitations to be sent out for the afternoon ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Masire, who has been president for 17 years, was expected to
hand the reins of power to his Vice President and Finance
Minister, Festus Mogae before the end of the year, said SAPA.
</P>
<P>
Under the constitution, Mogae could succeed Masire at least
until the next election, which must be held in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Masire had consistently refused to step down. But in an
interview two weeks ago he made it clear that he would not go
beyond the 1999 election.
</P>
<P>
The newly amended constitution limited the president's term to
10 years. But Masire could serve two five-year terms after the
1999 elections since the measure was not retroactive.
</P>
<P>
He made it clear that he would not do so, saying: "I am not
going to carry on for another 10 years. The law is not
retroactive... but that would not be the letter of the law, nor
the spirit of the law."
</P>
<P>
Masire expressed his confidence in the leadership of his
party, the Botswana Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
"There are equally competent, if not more competent, people to
take the initiative. I am confident that they'll push this
country ahead."
</P>
<P>
He also promised not to interfere with the running of the
country.
</P>
<P>
Asked how he saw Botswana after 1999, Masire said: "It depends
on the outcome of the election. If we win, as I wish and hope we
shall, we are blessed with having some very good men in the
leadership of the Botswana Democratic Party even if I'm not
there." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
