<HEADLINE> China Seeks More Foreign Investment for Primary Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 10 (Xinhua) -- China will continue to
encourage foreign direct investment (FDI) for projects related to
new agricultural technology and primary industries, including the
energy, transportation and major raw materials sectors.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government will accelerate the construction of
agricultural infrastructure in order to improve production
conditions, with priority placed on water conservancy," according
to Song Mi, director of the Fixed Assets Department of the State
Planning Commission. Song made the remarks during the ongoing
international seminar on China's Investment policies and project
financing.
</P>
<P>
Song said the government will place greater emphasis on
environmental protection in order to achieve a sustainable
economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, water conservancy and environmental protection will
both hold an important position in terms of investment and
construction, and foreign friends are welcome to participate in
related fields," said Song.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government considers primary industries as the
focal point of the state's investment program and has drafted a
series of preferential policies to facilitate investment in the
sector.
</P>
<P>
Song noted that China's investment in the capital construction
of the primary industries has surpassed one trillion yuan since
the early 1990s, with said figure accounting for more than 40
percent of the national total.
</P>
<P>
The fact that China will maintain rapid economic growth in the
coming years calls for increased investments in primary
industries, said Song adding that the government will continue to
carry out effective policies to support development of the sector.
</P>
<P>
The 3-day seminar, sponsored by the State Planning Commission,
has attracted delegates from more than 20 member countries of the
Berne Union, as well as Chinese officials and
experts. Participants will discuss China's economic policies, the
nation's investment environment and the prospects for primary
industries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
