<HEADLINE> Nordic and Baltic Prime Ministers to Meet in Helsinki </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, November 10 (Xinhua)-- Prime Ministers of five
Nordic and three Baltic countries will meet today in Helsinki,
Finland, to discuss European integration and regional economic
cooperation, according to local press reports here.
</P>
<P>
Economic stability in the Baltic states is seen on both sides
of the Atlantic as a key ingredient in regional security.
</P>
<P>
The prime ministers will also discuss Russian President Boris
Yeltsin's proposal made on October 24 to engage the Nordic and
Baltic states in a pact covering the region's economy, ecology and
military security.
</P>
<P>
The proposal, which is viewed by some as an attempt to prevent
a further enlargement of NATO, has not received much enthusiasm in
the Nordic and Baltic countries. Swedish Deputy Foreign Minister
Pierre Schori said his country sees "no need to link confidence
building to a regional security arrangement."
</P>
<P>
The Nordic and Baltic countries are Finland, Sweden, Denmark,
Norway, Iceland, Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
