<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Vows to Stick to Bank Liquidation Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government said
today that it will adhere to its decision of liquidating 16 ailing
banks to uphold the law and restore the country's credibility in
the international community and accept the consequences of that
decision.
</P>
<P>
"Our country is a law-based state, so if one feels actions are
being taken to their detriment, he or she is free to pursue it
through legal channels," Finance Minister Mar'ie Muhammad told a
plenary session of the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that the government had followed proper
procedures, including issuing advance warnings, before finally
deciding to close the 16 banks on November 1.
</P>
<P>
The minister also called on the owners, management and
employees of the liquidated banks to cooperate with the government
and obey government rules on the matter.
</P>
<P>
Mar'ie pointed out that the government closed the banks for
insufficient assets to cover their obligations, particularly
because of bad debts.
</P>
<P>
The weight of bad debts that burdened the banks made them
unable to cover their expenses so they suffered losses, the amount
of which ballooned year by year.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the banks' ability to collect funds from
their clients had weakened, causing their finances to mostly
depend on the short-term money market, with high interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The accumulation of the losses was very big, causing capital to
drop below zero. Warnings and proposals for improvement issued by
the Bank of Indonesia, the central bank, received less than
positive response from the management of the banks.
</P>
<P>
The liquidation of the 16 banks constituted an important
element in the government's program to restore health to the
banking sector, he added.
</P>
<P>
To overcome the current monetary crisis, which has badly hit
the country's economy, the Indonesian government has taken many
measures including seeking 23 billion U.S. dollars in aid from the
International Monetary Fund.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971110.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's External Reserves Hit $8bn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's external reserves,
which doubled in less than two years, hit the mark of eight
billion U.S. Dollars in September this year.
</P>
<P>
This stretched the nation's capacity to finance its imports to
over six months, a source at the Finance Ministry said at the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
The reserves were quadrupled in 1996 after going up to 4.07
billion Dollars from 1.44 billion Dollars from 1995, according to
statistics.
</P>
<P>
Since 1996, the task of building the external reserves has
been a priority of the government.
</P>
<P>
The positive outlook in the reserves position was accounted
for by the tight fiscal and monetary policies of the federal
government, which led to general mood of improvement in the
country's macro-economic indicators.
</P>
<P>
Inflation rate went down to 12 percent in August this year
from 28 percent at the end of last year and 72.8 percent in
December 1995.
</P>
<P>
Exchange rate dropped from 82.5 Naira to one U.S. Dollar to 80
Naira to one dollar las week. The rate had stabilized at 82.5
Naira for nearly three months.
</P>
<P>
The government had earlier targeted an exchange rate of 75
Naira to one Dollar for December 1997.
</P>
<P>
Increases in price and volume of oil exports, which earn more
than 80 percent of the country's foreign exchange, also added to
the stock of the external reservers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the external debt stock declined to about 27
billion Dollars from 28 billion as at the end of last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
