<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Air Force Chopper Downed by Rebel Missile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, November 10 (Xinhua) -- A Mi-24 attack helicopter of
the Sri Lankan Air Force was brought down by a rebel missile this
morning at Kokkilai Lagoon in the northeastern coastal area, with
its two pilots killed, the military said this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
A military spokesman said the incident took place when the
ill-fated chopper was escorting three Mi-17 helicopters
transporting troops from Vavuniya to Elephant Pass in the north.
</P>
<P>
The fleet left Vavuniya at 11:15 a.m. local time. The escort
chopper observed four boats of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam (LTTE) at sea off the Kokkilai coast and decided to change
course to ensure the safety of the troops on board.
</P>
<P>
When the choppers were over the Kokkilai Lagoon, the LTTE
rebels fired two missiles, one of which hit the Mi-24 and brought
it with its two pilots and two gunners down into the lagoon. A
Mi-17 chopper sustained damage to the rotor and tail boom due to
the explosion of the missile.
</P>
<P>
The other choppers activated the anti-missile system and evaded
the second missile.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Army and Navy personnel rushed to the lagoon
and rescued one pilot and two gunners from the crashed Mi-24.
</P>
<P>
But the pilot later succumbed to his injuries in hospital. The
Defense Ministry told Xinhua that the other pilot on board the
Mi-24 which sank in the waters of the lagoon was presumed dead.
</P>
<P>
The three Mi-17s later returned safely to Vavuniya with all
soldiers on board. Military sources said each of the choppers
could carry as many as 35 soldiers in addition to its crew.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has been fighting for a separate state of their own in
the north and east of the country since 1983. Missile attacks by
the rebels have caused great losses of aircraft and personnel to
the military.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
