<HEADLINE> Philips Semiconductors to Build New Plant in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Philips Semiconductors
announced today that it will begin construction of a new test and
assembly plant for integrated circuits (IC) at Calamba, some 50
kilometers south of the Philippine capital of Manila.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement available here, the company said
construction of the new plant will begin this month and phase I of
the project will be completed in the first quarter of 1999 while
phase II will start one year later, depending on market
conditions.
</P>
<P>
Philips Semiconductor plans to employ about 2,000 people when
the plant, the second one in the Philippines, is fully
operational, it said.
</P>
<P>
Calamba will be Philips Semiconductors' third IC test and
assembly plant. The other two are located in Kaohsiung, China's
Taiwan Province, and the Thai capital of Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
The company said the new plant will assemble and test
integrated circuits produced by Philips Semiconductors' IC
fabrication facilities in Europe and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Philips Semiconductors, a division of Philips Electronics NV,
headquartered in Eindhoven, the Netherlands, is the ninth largest
semiconductor supplier and the third largest supplier of discretes
in the world.  
</P>
</TEXT>
