<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The following are business
briefs from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Germany is to provide Jordan with a soft loan of 43
million Deutch marks (about 25 million U.S. dollars) to finance
the construction of a water network project in Amman,
semi-official Jordan Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
An agreement signed by both sides on Sunday stipulates that
the German Bank for Development and Reconstruction will finance
part of the project for replacing the worn-out water network which
runs some 500 kilometers within the city.
</P>
<P>
The whole project is expected to cost 24 million dinars (about
34 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Jordanian Minister of Planning Rima
Khalaf and German Ambassador to Amman Peter Mende.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The United Nations Security Council's Sanctions
Committee on Iraq has approved requests by a number of Jordanian
firms to export goods worth 1.74 million U.S. dollars to Iraq
under the oil-for-food deal, semi-official Jordan Times reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The latest approval allows Jordan to export more medicines,
table salt and galvanized metal, the paper quoted an unidentified
source in the Jordanian Ministry of Industry and Trade as saying.
</P>
<P>
Last September, Iraq concluded contracts with 35 Jordanian
industrial institutions to purchase goods worth more than 83
million dollars within the framework of the oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Since Israel and Canada began implementing a free
trade agreement in January, bilateral trade volume in the first
eight months of the year reached 295 million U.S. dollars, a 50
percent increase over that of the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post newspaper today reported that in the period,
Israel's imports from Canada totaled 95 million dollars and its
exports to Canada amounted to 200 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The free trade agreement's purpose is to substantially
increase trade in both directions, and it seems to be doing
that," said Canada's Ambassador to Israel David Berger Sunday in
Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the upcoming visit to Israel by Canadian Foreign
Minister Lloyd Axworthy is also expected to boost the bilateral
trade dramatically, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
