<HEADLINE> Muslim Rebels Optimistic on Peace Talks With Manila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The rebel Moro Islamic
Liberation Front (MILF) today expressed optimism that its talks
with the Philippine government this week will remove obstacles to
the implementation of an earlier cease-fire agreement.
</P>
<P>
Ghadzali Jaafar, MILF deputy chairman for political affairs,
was quoted by local television reports as saying he believed the
upcoming meeting will lead to the signing of a document on
cease-fire ground rules, key to the implementation of the truce
signed by the two sides on July 18.
</P>
<P>
On November 12-13, peace panels from the MILF and the
government will meet in the city of Marawi in central Mindanao to
discuss the much-delayed drafting of ground rules and guidelines
for carrying out the accord on the cessation of hostilities
between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Abdulhaziz Minbantas, MILF deputy chairman for internal
affairs, will replace Jaafar as MILF chief peace negotiator in the
Marawi meeting, according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
Jaafar said the MILF has already prepared its proposed agenda
for the meeting, the eighth round of their exploratory peace talks
with the government.
</P>
<P>
Efforts by the MILF and the government to forge an agreement on
ground rules regarding the comprehensive cease-fire accord failed
due to two incidents last month -- the controversial public
execution by the MILF of alleged criminals and an attack by two
alleged Arab terrorists on a military camp in central Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, a splinter faction of the Moro National Liberation
Front (MNLF), is currently the largest anti-government force in
the country, with an estimated membership of nearly 12,000.
</P>
<P>
The MILF and the extremist Abu Sayyaf are the two remaining
Muslim rebel groups fighting the government troops. The MNLF
signed a peace agreement with Manila in September last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
