<HEADLINE> National Judges College Opens in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The National Judges College,
China's first institute of higher education designed to train senior
judges, formally opened today in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The college evolved from a part-time law school for court
officials and a training center for senior judges.
</P>
<P>
The new college will actively expand exchanges with the outside
world and draw on advanced foreign judicial practices and
expertise to train Chinese judges.
</P>
<P>
The institution will also serve as a window for displaying the
image of Chinese judges and publicizing the nation's judicial
activities and legal construction.
</P>
<P>
The college, which will accommodate 400 trainees, will be
staffed by outstanding teachers and will offer regular lectures by
experienced judges.
</P>
<P>
Supreme People's Court President Ren Jianxin will serve as
president of the college.
</P>
<P>
Ren attended today's founding ceremony and noted that the
college will greatly promote China's judicial reform and help
raise the quality of judges.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin inscribed the name of the
college.
</P>
<P>
Qiao Shi, chairman of the National People's Congress
Standing Committee, and State Councillors Luo Gan and Li Guixian
also attended the ceremony.  
</P>
</TEXT>
