<HEADLINE> Singapore: Southeast Asia Can Rebound From Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Southeast Asia will be able
to rebound from the currency and stock market crisis after a
period of adjustment and consolidation, Singapore Trade and
Industry Minister Lee Yock Suan said here today.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the recent economic difficulties in the region, the
prospect for future growth remains bright for the ASEAN countries
especially after a period of adjustment and consolidation," the
minister told the opening session of the inaugural ASEAN-European
Union Partenariat.
</P>
<P>
The Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) now consists
of nine countries in the region -- Indonesia, Malaysia, Thailand,
the Philippines, Singapore, Brunei, Vietnam, Myanmar and Laos.
</P>
<P>
"Although the financial sectors in some ASEAN countries have to
make tough adjustments, there are few structural impediments to
future growth which is expected to remain high after this period
of correction," Lee added.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, he pointed out that the currency devaluation has
made the exports from ASEAN countries more competitive in world
markets, especially those products with high local contents.
</P>
<P>
The minister also noted that the ASEAN economies have high
saving rates and their governments have invested heavily in
education and infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
On the just-launched first ASEAN-EU Partenariat, which aims to
promote long-term business and trade ties between the small and
medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) from both regions, he called on
companies to form strategic alliances in order to be regionally
competitive.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN-EU Partenariat is one of the largest business
matching meetings involving some 500 SMEs from ASEAN and European
Union members.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
