<HEADLINE> French Utility Service Company Opens China Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Group Generale des Eaux, a
world leader in utility services, announced the opening of its
China office today as part of its effort to build closer economic
relations with the nation.
</P>
<P>
"The office is key to our China strategy." said Jean-Marie
Messier, the company's chairman and chief executive officer. "We
are committed to establishing a long-term partnership with China
based on mutual trust and the fulfillment of common interests."
</P>
<P>
The group has invested more than 780 million US dollars in
China since early 1980s, and plans to increase investments in the
nation's water distribution, energy management, power generation
and waste treatment sectors.
</P>
<P>
The group has constructed 20 drinking water and wastewater
treatment plants in cities including Luoyang, Qiqihar, Tonghua,
Huizhou, Xi'an and Shanghai. It has also signed a 30 million US
dollar contract to operate the existing Tianjin Water Plant which
serves four million people.
</P>
<P>
The company also operate four power plants across China, and
has signed a 400 million US dollar contract for civil engineering
services at Daya Bay, one of the world's largest nuclear power
plants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
