<DOCNO> XIE19971110.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Markets Offer Opportunities For Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The current volatility in
Asian financial markets would calm over the next 12 months,
offering new opportunities for Australia's domestic fund managers
to invest in Asian interest rate markets, a manager of an
investment firm says.
</P>
<P>
Over the past year, domestic funds have been reducing their
domestic fixed interest asset allocations in line with falling
interest rates, said investment director Michael Clarke of
Equitilink Investment Management.
</P>
<P>
And with cash in hand the search by funds for better investment
opportunities was on, he said. "There will be ongoing shocks,
surprises and uncertainties coming out of the region over the next
six to nine months at least," Clarke said of Southeast Asia at a
conference on debt capital markets in Sydney, the Australia
Associated Press reported today.
</P>
<P>
"There will be a period of confusion while they reorganize, and
then we expect them to come out of this. We should see that in a
year or two things will certainly be more stable," Clarke said.
</P>
<P>
Clarke said investment rates in Southeast Asia offered
potential for "tremendous rewards" over a medium-term horizon.
</P>
<P>
"The yield there is very attractive...they are very, very
attractive yields," Clarke said, referring to short-term interest
rates of between 10-20 percent.
</P>
<P>
In Thailand, short-term rates are around 15 percent, compared
to 5.0 percent in Australia, Clarke said, "So if you are prepared
to look at it...tremendous rewards are possible in the next five
years."
</P>
<P>
But this outlook did not ignore glaring inefficiencies in some
Southeast Asian markets. For instance, some countries do not have
a clear timetable for the release of economic data and this can
disadvantage bond traders' views of what is happening in the
economy.
</P>
<P>
"There are many inefficiencies, there are many problems, and
you need to be alert and not trust almost anything you get but the
compensation for this is a 1,000 basis point yield pick-up," said
Clarke.
</P>
<P>
As Clarke saw, yields in Australia were likely to remain low
for at least another four to five years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971110.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Modernization Project for Karachi Port Approved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani government has
approved the second five-year modernization project for the
Karachi Port.
</P>
<P>
The five-year project, formulated by the Karachi Port, is
expected to start in 1998 at a cost of 350 million U.S. dollars,
said Khalid M. Mir, chairman of the Karachi Port Trust (KPT).
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the inauguration of the Jinnah Bridge in Karachi
today, Mir said the cost of the five-year plan has a 50-percent
foreign currency financing from the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The plan includes improvement and deepening of the navigable
channel; procurement of harbor craft like tugs, pilot boats,
dredges, survey launches and pollution control equipment; setting
up of a new hazardous cargo terminal with related equipment; and
construction of a container freight station, according to Mir.
</P>
<P>
He said preparations for various schemes under this plan are
under way and physical implementation will begin at the end of
1998.
</P>
<P>
The KPT chairman said that at present the Karachi Port handles
about 75 percent of the country's maritime cargo trade and
supports the livelihood of more than 100,000 people by employing
about 20,000 port workers.
</P>
<P>
During the 1996-97 fiscal year, the port handled 24.2 million
tons of cargo carried by more than 1,700 ships with almost zero
off-port waiting time, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
