<DOCNO> XIE19971110.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Call for Better Social Care Caused by Family Tragedy in Macao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The tragedy of Macao family in
which the parents killed themselves following their two children's
death has touched off a call for more social care.
</P>
<P>
Kao Chak-keung, 39, a decoration worker, and his wife Tong In
Chan, 35, were found to have hanged themselves together on Sunday
morning after their son and daughter died of a fire on Saturday
morning.
</P>
<P>
The incident has caused a wide-spread call to improve social
care and psychiatric help for those needed.
</P>
<P>
While giving front-paged coverage of the incident, all eight
local Chinese newspapers have carried some form of editorials
today, either urging the government to establish psychiatric aide
center, or provide more care to those needed.
</P>
<P>
The Macao Daily News said in a commentary that many
lower-income families commonly leave their children unattended
while both parents are out working, posing great danger for the
kids. But that is the only choice they can make.
</P>
<P>
"The first incident of the death of the children has sounded
the alarm for negligence," it said. "But again negligence has
caused the death of the couple. That teaches us a profound
lesson."
</P>
<P>
The Va Kio newspaper said that the Government should pay more
attention to the caring of children in families of double working
parents and single-parent families.
</P>
<P>
In addition, it said that social psychiatric help center
should be established to meet the needs of those suffered from
natural disasters. It also urges residents to help each other to
prevent similar tragedies.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, social workers said that the tragedy means a warning
that Macao needs better psychiatric crisis service and more
professional psychiatrists.
</P>
<P>
Top executives of the Macao Charity, the Macao Better Family
Promotion Association, and some members of the Macao Legislative
Assembly, all made remarks urging the Government and social
welfare centers to establish a quick-action mechanism offering
necessary social help.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
