<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian PM on Constitutional Convention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister
John Howard today urged republicans and monarchists to use next
year's constitutional convention to find an alternative to the
current system of government.
</P>
<P>
Howard said there is no point in republicans and monarchists
using the convention, scheduled for February next year, to try to
persuade each other to change their mind on the main issue.
</P>
<P>
Instead, Howard said they should try and thrash out an
agreement on an alternate system of government, which could then
be put to a national vote.
</P>
<P>
"There's no point at the convention in convinced republicans
trying to persuade convinced anti-republicans to change their mind
on the threshold issue," he said over the Nine Network.
</P>
<P>
"I think the convention should spend its time, both republicans
and non-republicans alike, trying to reach agreement on the
alternative to the present system."
</P>
<P>
The Australian Republican Movement (ARM) welcomed Howard's
comments, claiming that the prime minister has rejected the
negative approach being taken by the monarchists.
</P>
<P>
But Australians for Constitutional Monarchy (ACM) said there
would be no negotiations on any alternative to the current
government system.
</P>
<P>
"There will be no negotiation by no-republic-ACM delegates on
any change to our current constitutional arrangements and all
republican alternatives will be refuted in the strongest of
terms," ACM Executive Director Kerry Jones said in a statement,
available here today.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
