<HEADLINE> Chinese, Russian Presidents Hold Talks (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jiang pointed to the solid foundation for Sino-Russian economic
and trade relations, and said the two sides should make even
greater efforts to fully tap their respective vast potentials and
advantages by creating new fields and forms of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"Breakthroughs should be made in long-term cooperation related
to large and medium-sized projects," said Jiang, adding that the
two sides are fully capable of conducting large-scale cooperation
in such fields as petroleum, natural gas, electricity, aerospace,
machine-building and high technology.
</P>
<P>
He said that China will actively approach related efforts, and
stressed that the Commission for Regular Meetings Between the
Heads of Government of Russia and China will play an important
role in promoting economic and trade cooperation between the two
countries. He noted that enterprises from the two countries should
expand contacts in order to find partners for cooperative ventures.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin pointed to the high complementarity of the Russian and
Chinese economies. He said the two countries have entered a number
of economic cooperation and trade projects and have put forward
many proposals in this regard. The two sides should further
strengthen cooperation and implement the proposals as soon as
possible, according to the Russian President.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders expressed full confidence in further promoting
bilateral trade through continued joint efforts, with both
expressing their belief that it is perfectly possible for the
Sino-Russian trade volume to hit 20 billion U.S. dollars by the
year 2000.
</P>
