<HEADLINE> China, S. Africa Sign Half-Billion Dollar Accords </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 10 (Xinhua) -- China and South Africa
signed 18 trade and investment contracts and protocols totaling
540 million U.S. Dollars in Johannesburg this morning.
</P>
<P>
The agreements covered finance, trade and investment, said
Zhou Jie, an official with China's Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The largest deal was an agreement between China's Northeastern
Power Transmission and Transformation Group and South Africa's
Eskom company to import from China power transmission and
transformation equipment worth 130 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The two countries agreed to set up 12 joint ventures in South
Africa, Shi Guangsheng, head of a massive Chinese trade and
economic delegation, told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Shi, who is deputy foreign trade minister, said the agreements
sealed today represented only part of the trade and economic
achievements between the two countries and that more deals are
under way.
</P>
<P>
He said these agreements were the starting point and provided
a foundation for future cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
With the establishment of diplomatic relations, he said, there
would be more trade and economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela said last November that
his country would sever ties with Taiwan and establish full
diplomatic relations with the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
He said the agreements will contribute to South Africa's
economic development, job creation and improvement of housing
conditions.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese delegation, made up of more than 100 trade and
economic officials and representatives of some 50 leading Chinese
companies, arrived here on Wednesday for an 11-day visit.
</P>
<P>
They will also tour Pretoria, Cape Town and Durban, where they
will continue to have talks with South African government
officials and entrepreneurs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
