<HEADLINE> ADB to Increase Support in Social Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The Manila-based Asian
Development Bank (ADB) said today that it will substantially
expand its policies in addressing social development issues in the
Asia-Pacific.
</P>
<P>
The ADB will develop new approaches in designing projects to
strengthen the bank's ability to support social development in the
region, ADB President Mitsuo Sato told the opening of the Fifth
Asian-Pacific Ministerial Conference on Social Development today.
</P>
<P>
About 300 government ministers and officials from 32
Asian-Pacific countries and regions are meeting here to review the
implementation of the Manila Action Agenda on Social Development
for the region.
</P>
<P>
In face of the current financial crisis in the region, the ADB
has adopted measures to protect indigenous peoples and ensure that
its loan program will not adversely affecting the poor, Sato said.
</P>
<P>
In keeping with themes in the Manila action agenda, Sato said,
the ADB continues to focus its assistance on the health and
education sectors to help the poor.
</P>
<P>
The ADB also provides aid for improvements in urban services,
slum upgrading, and low cost housing, Sato said.
</P>
<P>
The ADB will increase support for micro-finance and is
currently preparing an action plan to make its operations more
effective so that the poor can have access to capital, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
