<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Strong buying in resource
stocks and relative stability in Asian trading pushed the
Australian sharemarket higher today in defiance of predictions
that it would head for the opposite direction.
</P>
<P>
The All Ordinaries Index rose 8.2 points to close at 2521.6
although it opened lower on the back of Friday night's fall on
Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said takeover rumors surrounding some major resource
stocks, including MIM and WMC, were responsible for strong buying
interest in these stocks today.
</P>
<P>
"With some of the resource stocks as low as they are, there
were some takeover rumors on Friday and it looks as though some of
that has flowed through to today's market and perhaps some people
are suggesting some of those stocks are pretty under-priced," a
Brisbane broker said.
</P>
<P>
The All Resources Index rose 15.6 points to 1171.6 with WMC
leading the gainers by improving 29 cents to 5.54 Australian
dollars on a turnover of 4.3 million shares.
</P>
<P>
BHP gained 51 cents to 14.78 Australian dollars on a turnover
of 5.3 million shares while Rio Tinto rose 5 cents to 17.05
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Gold stocks fell as the bullion price dropped to 308.75 U.S.
dollars per ounce compared with Friday's close of 312.35.
</P>
<P>
The All Industrials Index improved marginally, up half a point
to 4226.2.
</P>
<P>
Banking stocks were mixed. National Australia Bank rose 40
cents while ANZ dropped 19 cents, Commonwealth 18 cents and St.
George 21 cents.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 234.71 million shares worth 747.21
million Australian dollars (523.04 million U.S. dollars). Falls
outnumbered rises by 720 to 428.  
</P>
</TEXT>
