<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Firms Eye Tanzania's Furniture Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, November 10 (Xinhua) -- South African and
Zimbabwean wood and furniture companies have been exploring ways
of setting up firms in Tanzania, which imports much of its
top-quality furniture from Kenlyawean, Europe and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
Bell Equipment and ING Barings from South Africa and
Zimbabwe's Border Timbers have made formal contracts with
Tanzanian timber and wood companies, some of them soon to be
privatized, for possible joint partnership deals.
</P>
<P>
An official of the Parastatal Sector Reform Commission and
Salvatore Nindi of Zenith Furniture company here told The East
African weekly that two senior officials from South Africa have
come to Tanzania for discussions on setting up plants to produce
quality furniture.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposed terms, the South Africans will establish
small modern plants worth about 2.4 million U.S. Dollars in Dar
es Salaam to make top quality wood products.
</P>
<P>
Border Timbers, one of the biggest such companies in Africa,
is also interested in setting up plants in Tanzania, the weekly
said today.
</P>
<P>
Nindi said: "Mr Stock Niersk of Bell Equipment was astonished
to hear that many diplomatic offices are equipped with imported
furniture in a country endowed with all sorts of timber."
</P>
<P>
Because most of these imports are duty-free, Nindi said,
Tanzania loses in more ways than one, including the loss of job
opportunities and the transfer of skills that would be provided
by the new investors.
</P>
<P>
Imported wood products from Europe and Kenya are 50 percent
cheaper than comparable Tanzanian-made goods, Nindi said, giving
the example of an imported Danish-made office chair priced at
6.50 US Dollars (FOB) compared to a Tanzanian hardwood chair
which would sell at a price between 18 and 25 US Dollars in Dar
es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
Up to the late 1980s, diplomatic missions used to order
household and office furniture from local wood and furniture
marts. However, the trend changed with the fall of the timber and
wood industry and the liberalization of the market.
</P>
<P>
The objective of Tanzania Wood Industry, a holding company of
six wood and timber subsidiaries, is to raise production of
softwood to 253,982 cubic meters by the year 2020. 
</P>
</TEXT>
