<DOCNO> XIE19971110.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Cash Selling Rate Tops 1,000 Won </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar's cash selling
rate topped the 1,000-won level for the first time Monday, opening
the era of 1,000 won per dollar.
</P>
<P>
Largely hit by psychological factors, the won started the day's
trading at 985.00 won per dollar, down 5.10 won from last week's
close of 979.90 won.
</P>
<P>
It then plunged to an all-time intraday low of 999.00 won,
mainly because of strong demand for U.S. dollars among domestic
exporters to settle their imports and foreign investors' continued
low confidence in the South Korean financial market.
</P>
<P>
At 9:50 a.m., Korea Exchange Bank (KEB) posted again the day's
dollar basic rate and cash selling rate at 999 won and 1,013.98
won, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the central bank's intervention, the won slightly
recovered to 996 won but fell again back to 998.50 won.
</P>
<P>
"The won's continued fall is mainly attributable to foreign
investor's waning confidence in the domestic financial market,"
said Lee Kang-nam, assistant governor of the Bank of Korea (BOK).
</P>
<P>
To make things worse, the international credit standing of
Korean financial institutions fell significantly, mainly owing to
a spate of large corporate bankruptcies and the consequential
reduction of their borrowing of foreign capital. This resulted in
a dire shortage of foreign currency.
</P>
<P>
The central bank, which has repeatedly receded from previous
resistance levels over the past three weeks, however, said it
would not allow the won to decline below the 1,000-mark.
</P>
<P>
Government officials also said that the government would not
let any South Korean financial institutions default on foreign
debts, while it would work out steps to help foreign
currency-strapped merchant banks.
</P>
<P>
The sharp depreciation of the won against the dollar has led to
higher inflation since the country depends heavily on the import
of raw materials.
</P>
<P>
The falling won has also sparked a sharp decline in stock
prices on the Korea Stock Exchange as a slew of foreign investors
try to dump their shares in efforts to avoid exchange losses
resulting from the won's steep depreciation, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
