<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stock Trading Declines Amidst Rising Indices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Total turnover on the
Shanghai Stock Exchange (SSE) declined in October, with two major
stock indices ending the month higher than in September.
</P>
<P>
Exchange statistics show that the benchmark Composite Stock
Index for October closed at 1,180.39 points, up 8.23 percent on
September, with the SSE-30 Index, which is based on 30 blue chip
stocks, finising at 3,671.62 points, a monthly rise of 7.56
percent.
</P>
<P>
Stock trading was generally slow in October, with the monthly
volume falling 13.47 percent to 67.75 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Both prices and trading for B shares, stocks issued in China
but reserved for overseas investors, fell last month.
</P>
<P>
The index tracking B shares closed October at 63.99 points,
down 16.14 percent on September, with the turnover for B shares
plunging by more than 20 percent to 1.26 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Official figures also indicate that interest rate reductions
effective on October 23 boosted transactions for treasury bonds,
with the total volume hitting 100 billion yuan for the second
month in a row. Spot trading surged 65.5 percent to 32.4 billion
yuan, with the volume for repurchased bonds jumping more than 30
percent to 86.9 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Trading in funds reached 1.6 billion yuan in October, up 46
million yuan on the previous month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
