<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Ranks Second in Asia's Retail Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong ranked second only
to Japan in Asia's retails sales on a per capita basis in 1996,
reaching 4,254 US dollars, Secretary for Trade and Industry Denise
Yue said today.
</P>
<P>
The city took the 15th place across the globe, according to the
World Competitiveness Yearbook of 1997, Yue added.
</P>
<P>
Shopping is one of the most popular activities in Hong Kong as
people became more affluent, she told the 51st General Assembly of
the International Group of Department Stores.
</P>
<P>
According to a World Bank study, Hong Kong's per capita income
was 24,600 US dollars in 1996, among the top 10 in the world.
</P>
<P>
The tourism industry also contributed to the flourishing retail
business, as Hong Kong is one of the most popular tourist
destinations in Asia, she said.
</P>
<P>
Yue noted that the retail and wholesale industry is the second
largest service sector in Hong Kong in terms of sales turnover,
number of establishments and employment.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the retail sector alone employed some 200,000 people
in some 52,000 establishments. Total sales reached 28.7 billion US
dollars last year, she added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
