<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Down but Off Lows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 4 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar finished
lower today against the U.S. dollar but up from its intraday lows
as the local stockmarket ended in positive territory.
</P>
<P>
The local unit settled at 69.58 U.S. cents, from 69.79
previously.
</P>
<P>
The market was wary this morning, expecting that Friday's
decline on Wall Street would translate into a weaker equity
market.
</P>
<P>
But the Australian Stock Exchange's All Ordinaries Index
finished up 8.2 points to 2,521.6 after turning around an
initially softer start to the session.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar started the day at 69.23 U.S. cents
before short covering by a large offshore bank pushed it up to
69.75 U.S. cents, its peak for the day.
</P>
<P>
But it was pressured back from that level into a 69.50-69.65
U.S. cent band as the price of gold fell during trading in the
Asian time zone.
</P>
<P>
Rothschild Australia treasury manager Paul Macarounas said the
Australian dollar could this week slide into the 68 U.S. cent
band.
</P>
<P>
"The range will move down in blocks for the rest of the week,"
Macarounas said. "Starting off the week with this sort of levels I
think we'll test the downside and see whether we can slip past
those recent lows of 68.2 U.S. cents."
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar finished also at 86.21 Japanese yen, from
86.34 previously, and at 1.1912 Deutsche marks, from 1.2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
