<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Spy Plane Leaves Iraqi Airspace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. U-2 spy plane has
left Iraq's airspace after three hours of flight over the country
without any incident happened.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi military said in a statement that its troops were
standing by to gun down the plane, which was flying outside the
range of their missiles.
</P>
<P>
The U-2 surveillance plane entered Iraqi airspace at 8:21 local
time (0521 GMT) from Saudi Arabia on Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has threatened to shoot down the aircraft, accusing that
the United States has used the flights to garner information and
select targets for attacks against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The American plane was used by the United Nations Special
Commission on dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction for
monitoring missions.
</P>
<P>
It resumed flights over Iraq Monday in spite of Baghdad's
threat and its standoff with the United Nations over banning
Americans from U.N. inspection teams. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
