<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Early Sex Education Called for in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese education experts
have stressed that sex education at an early age is necessary in
Lebanese schools, local Daily Star newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
"Sex and health education should begin early in a child's life
and continue gradually each year as part of a child's development
and growth," said Wafica Mansour Doueiri, vice president of
Lebanon's Family Planning Association (FPA), at a day-long
workshop Sunday.
</P>
<P>
She said the FPA would attempt to find the proper means to
implement sex education in schools.
</P>
<P>
Faysal Qaq, a university professor, said that the latest U.N.
study found the more sex education students get at school the more
likely they are to have control of their sexual behavior and
less likely to be subjected to disease and pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
Qaq said that people must wake up and admit that students in
Lebanon, and around the world, are becoming sexually active at an
earlier age.
</P>
<P>
He added that there were no statistics on sexual activity in
Lebanon, but that an ongoing study of high school students showed
that a "good percentage of students are sexually active."
</P>
<P>
Qaq also highlighted the important role the government had in
collaborating with the media to raise awareness of sexually
transmitted diseases and protection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
