<HEADLINE> Hezbollah: Israel Attack Likely After Doha Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Hezbollah chief Sheikh
Hassan Nasrallah has said that he expected a major Israeli
military operation in south Lebanon, but not before the Doha
conference, the Daily Star reported today.
</P>
<P>
The secretary general of the Iranian-backed Shiite Muslim
militant group said at a gathering in northeast Lebanon Sunday that
Israel feared an immediate offensive would turn Arab countries
away from the planned fourth Middle East and North Africa economic
conference.
</P>
<P>
The Doha conference, which includes Arabs, Israelis and their
major trade partners in the world, is due to be held on November
16-18.
</P>
<P>
Nasrallah urged Arab nations to boycott the conference. "The
United States is unable to force other countries to attend," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Speculations have been high since reports appeared on Russian
Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov's alleged remarks during his
Middle East tour last month that Israeli troops would stage a
major military operation against Hezbollah in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah, or Party of God, has been fighting to end Israeli
occupation in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Nasrallah called on all Lebanese to join the
newly-established multi-confessional Lebanese Brigades to resist
Israeli invasion.
</P>
<P>
Last Monday Nasrallah announced the creation of the new
resistance group that would accept people regardless of their
religious or political affiliations.
</P>
<P>
"The telephone numbers through which people can join the
brigades have been busy ever since our announcement and this is
evidence of the people's confidence in Hezbollah's credibility,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated the resistance's determination to fight Israel's
occupation troops until the territory is liberated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
