<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 09:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Baghdad Seeks Fair Treatment, Not Confrontation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 10 (Xinhua) -- A ranking Iraqi diplomat here
has said Iraq does not seek confrontation with the U.N. but rather
wants a fair treatment and have the seven-year-old economic
sanctions lifted.
</P>
<P>
According to the Middle East News Agency today, Nabil Negm,
Iraq's chief delegate to the Cairo-based Arab League (AL), made
the remark on Sudan during a meeting with AL Assistant Secretary
General for Arab Affairs Ahmed Ben Holai.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq does not seek a confrontation with the U.N. Security
Council or UNSCOM, but only wants the world body to adopt a fair
stand to lift the siege imposed on Iraq," Negm said.
</P>
<P>
He said Iraq has had an objective cooperation with UNSCOM in
charge of eliminating Iraq's weapons of mass destruction over the
past six years and provided all information available.
</P>
<P>
"UNSCOM dismantled all Iraqi weapons and even destroyed some of
the civil installations and facilities needed by Iraq," he said.
</P>
<P>
But the U.S. has declared that Iraq's compliance with all U.N.
Security Council resolutions won't even lead to lifting sanctions,
Negm said.
</P>
<P>
Negm said the American policy has been adopted by the UNSCOM
and posed a real threat to the Arab national security.
</P>
<P>
The current confrontation is a product of Iraq's insistence
that it has satisfied U.N. demands to scrap weapons of mass
destruction and has allowed over 600 U.N. monitoring sessions
since 1991.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad is requesting the U.N. to fulfil its commitment to lift
the economic embargo imposed after Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait
which triggered the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Iraq barred Americans from taking part in U.N. weapons
inspections for the seventh day in a row Sunday and threatened to
shoot down American U-2 spy plane flying into Iraqi airspace.
</P>
<P>
Washington has said all options, including a military action,
is open to overturn the Iraqi defiance.
</P>
<P>
Negm said Baghdad called for dialogue with the Security Council
and UNSCOM and offered related proposals to U.N. Secretary General
Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
Those include holding dialogue under Annan's supervision and at
the presence of Iraqi experts to brief the U.N. chief on Iraq's
concerns and practices constituting a violation of Iraq's
sovereignty, he said.
</P>
<P>
He described continuation of international sanctions on Baghdad
as a "continuous aggression on the Iraqi people."
</P>
<P>
In an official letter to Arab League Secretary General Esmat
Abdul Maguid, Iraq suggested that an Arab facting-finding mission,
including countries at odds with Baghdad, be sent to Iraq to
refute American allegations.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister is to meet with Annan and argue its
side of the standoff before the U.N. Security Council, which meets
today to decide on next steps to end the crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971110.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 162 Arrested in Belgium After Protest Riot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Belgian police have arrested
162 youths, mostly immigrants, who were protesting against the
police shooting to death a Moroccan immigrant claimed to be a drug
dealer.
</P>
<P>
Local television RTBF reported today that the arrests were made
late Sunday within the Anderlecht district of Brussels, where the
youths were protesting against the administrative authorities.
</P>
<P>
The protesters, who acted at the call of the Labor Party of Belgium
(PTB) after the death of Said Charki in a local hospital, sieged the
administrative office of the district authorities.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old Moroccan youth was seriously wounded as he tried to
run away from a police manhunt.
</P>
<P>
Police sources said that the drug dealer, with 50 grams of heroin
in possession, rammed his BMW into a police car when police attempted
to arrest him in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
Said Charki died in hospital Friday after being hit by 15 bullets,
television reports said.
</P>
<P>
Belgian Interior Minister Johan Vande Lanotte said that the
violence over the weekend was unacceptable and that police were
ordered to take a tough line should riot burst out again.
</P>
<P>
"The reaction on Friday was condemnable but understandable,"
television reports quoted the interior minister as saying, "but it
became something else on Saturday and Sunday. It was agitated and
manipulated by drug dealers and traffickers."
</P>
<P>
Sunday's riot was the third in the country's recent history.
Similar events took place in the Molenbeek district of Brussels in
1995 and at Saint-Gilles back in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
