<DOCNO> XIE19971110.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Non-Beijing Natives Cooperative in On-going Census </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 10 (Xinhua) -- When she heard about the the
news of census on non-Beijing residents, Xu Hulan, who sells
clothes in Beijing's Fengtai District, asked her husband to
quickly bring her mother-in-law and children back to the capital
city.
</P>
<P>
On the first day of the project, Xu's family sat inside their
rented house, waiting for the surveyors to come.
</P>
<P>
"I have been in Beijing for nine years. I hope all my family
members can be registered," Xu said. "If the Beijing Municipal
Government gives preferential policies to the migrant population,
we all can benefit from them."
</P>
<P>
Wang Xilin, Xu's friend, was initially afraid of what might
happen as a result of the census: he has changed homes twice,
telling the surveyors that he was worried about being forced to
leave Beijing.
</P>
<P>
During the past several days, many non-Beijing natives have
placed high hopes on the project, while some have their
concerns. However, the majority changed their minds once they
clearly understood the purpose of the work, according to the
census-takers.
</P>
<P>
Tian Yumei, a surveyor in the Haidian District, has to repeat
time and again when she visits families of non-Beijing natives
that the city just wants an accurate number of migrant
population. "We are neither giving you Beijing permanent residence
certificates, nor driving you out of Beijing," she tells them.
</P>
<P>
An Boyu, a native from Jiangsu Province, who learned of the
census from newspapers and TV, is more active, saying members of
the migrant population should take the initiative to register
themselves. "It is our duty to do so."
</P>
<P>
An not only registered on his own, he asks his employees to do
likewise.
</P>
<P>
People like An helped a lot in carrying out the census, which
ends on November 15, surveyor Tian Yumei said. A census official
in charge of the work said that more than 90 percent of
non-Beijing natives are cooperative.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the aim of the census is to obtain an
accurate number of migrants living in the city, which will help
the local government to deal with wide range of matters.
</P>
<P>
Results of the census will help the Beijing Municipal
Government when it comes to making plans for economic development,
urban construction, providing facilities and better serving all
city residents.
</P>
<P>
Surveyors said that most non-Beijing natives are concerned
about whether Beijing can provide a stable, safe environment for
living and working. They also ask to be treated fairly and with
respect and want their children to receive proper education.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971110.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Residents Call for Better Social Care after Family Tragedies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The incident has caused a wide-spread call to improve social
care and psychiatric help for those in need.
</P>
<P>
While giving front-paged coverage of the incident, all eight
local Chinese newspapers have carried some form of editorials
today, either urging the government to establish psychiatric aide
center, or provide more care to those in need.
</P>
<P>
The Macao Daily News said in a commentary that many
lower-income families usually leave their children unattended
while both parents are out working, posing great danger for the
kids. But that is the only choice they can make.
</P>
<P>
"The first incident of the death of the children has sounded
the alarm for negligence," it said. "But again negligence has
caused the death of the couple. That teaches us a profound
lesson."
</P>
<P>
The Va Kio newspaper said that the Government should pay more
attention to the caring of children in families of double working
parents and single-parent families.
</P>
<P>
In addition, it said that social psychiatric help center
should be established to meet the needs of those who have suffered
from natural disasters. It also urges residents to help each
other to prevent similar tragedies.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, social workers said that the tragedy means a warning
that Macao needs better psychiatric crisis service and more
professional psychiatrists.
</P>
<P>
Top executives of the Macao Charity, the Macao Better Family
Promotion Association, and some members of the Macao Legislative
Assembly, all expressed their opinions, urging the Government and
social welfare centers to establish a quick-action mechanism
offering necessary social help.  
</P>
</TEXT>
