<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN to Build Tech Center in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Industrial
Development Organization (UNIDO) will set up an innovation and
technology management center in Nairobi, Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Nation today quoted Kadress Vencatachellum, UNIDO
program manager, as saying Sunday that feasibility studies for
the center had been carried out.
</P>
<P>
Vencatachellum, who is based in Vienna, Austria, is in the
country to officiate the UNIDO-sponsored National Innovative
Prize Award Ceremony scheduled for tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
He said that UNIDO would next year start an engineering and
consultancy project in Kenya because the country is lack of
institutional capacity.
</P>
<P>
It was concerned that major engineering contracts like road
construction were won by foreign consultants, he added.
</P>
<P>
The UNIDO official pointed out that the National Innovative
Award was part of UNIDO's efforts to encourage industrialization
in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The program for the Award was started in 1995 and incorporates
Egypt, Ghana, Mauritius, Ethiopia, Zimbabwe and Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The program involves selecting the most innovative enterprises
nationally with nine winners getting the National Innovative
Prize Award in various categories.
</P>
<P>
The winners will participate in a regional prize award
ceremony later this month in Mauritius. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971110.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands of Beijing Residents Take Civil Service Exams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 10 (Xinhua) -- About 4,800 Beijing people
have taken the Beijing municipal government's civil service exams,
which will result in the hiring of some 40 civil servants.
</P>
<P>
Today's Beijing Daily reported that it is so far the
largest-scale civil servant invitation by the Beijing city
government.
</P>
<P>
Though many young people favor the higher salaries of
foreign-funded enterprise, more and more people are attracted to
the stability of government posts at various levels.
</P>
<P>
Beijing Daily reported that 92.1 percent of the applicants have
higher education, 48.8 percent of the total are women.
</P>
<P>
The daily said that the applicants also include 87 farmers who
applied for 31 posts in the local governments of the suburban
counties.
</P>
<P>
The three-part exam covers tests on comprehensive knowledge,
professional capabilities and knowledge of a specialized
field.  
</P>
</TEXT>
