<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong Pledges to Shed Poverty By 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, November 10 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong
Province has taken vigorous steps to eliminate poverty for its
remaining 600,000 poor by 2000, provincial source said.
</P>
<P>
According to deputy-governor Ou Guangyuan, the province has
supported 223,000 agricultural projects this year by appropriating
112.4 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Since 1987 the province has pooled funds topping 4.3 billion
yuan to aid poverty-stricken counties in the mountainous areas. By
the end of 1996, the population living on 500 yuan or below a year
had been reduced from 1.2 million in 1994 to 600,000.
</P>
<P>
A provincial source said the province's output in rural areas
totaled 666.5 billion yuan in 1996, with average annual per capita
incomes for farmers hitting 3,183 yuan, which is expected to reach
4,000 yuan by 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
