<DOCNO> XIE19971110.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 08:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Americans in UNIKOM Move to Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Americans working with
the United Nations Iraq-Kuwait Observation Mission (UNIKOM) have
been moved from the Iraqi territories to the Kuwait side of the
Demilitarized Zone (DMZ).
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by informed sources close to the mission,
according to local English daily Arab Times today.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the measure is precautionary in nature and
was taken last week after "some inquiries were made by Iraqi
officials about Americans working with the UNIKOM."
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the UNIKOM refused to confirm or deny the news.
</P>
<P>
The paper said the Americans have been instructed by the
UNIKOM command to carry out their patrolling duties only on
the Kuwaiti side of the DMZ.
</P>
<P>
The move is against the backdrop of the recent confrontation
between Iraq and the United Nations over Baghdad's insistence that
Americans be removed from U.N. weapons inspection teams in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraq banned all U.S. inspectors on the United Nations Special
Commission in charge of eliminating weapons of mass destruction in
the country, in response to U.N. resolution 1134 that threatened
new sanctions if Iraq continued hampering U.N. inspections.
</P>
<P>
Iraq also said it would shoot down American U-2 surveillance
plane flying over Iraq, but Washington warned of serious
consequences if the plane is fired on.
</P>
<P>
"To avoid any unwanted incident, the UNIKOM command decided to
move the Americans," the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of observers from several countries, including the
five permanent members of the U.N. Security Council, guard the
15-kilometer wide DMZ along the 200-kilometer long borders between
Iraq and Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The DMZ extends five kilometers inside Kuwait and 10 kilometers
inside Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
