<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Animal Husbandry Makes Strides in Jilin Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Animal husbandry in
northeastern China's Jilin Province, a leading grain producer, has
become a major means to propel its rural economy.
</P>
<P>
Jilin owns four million hectares of cultivated land. Corn output
makes up 75 percent of the province's grain output, and 16 percent
of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
After a long period of development, animal husbandry has
emerged as a pillar industry of the province's rural economy. The
province has also become a leading center of animal products.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the meat output of the province was 1.8
million tons in 1996. Large amounts of pork, chicken and beef,
have been transported to Beijing, Shanghai, Hong Kong and Japan.
</P>
<P>
In 2000, the value of animal husbandry will account for 49
percent of the province's total agricultural output, according to
a recent projection made by the provincial government.
</P>
<P>
The province is expected to be a leading producer of animal
products by 2010, and 40 percent of farmers' average income will
be derived from that sector.
</P>
<P>
To achieve its goal, the province has taken a series of
measures to open domestic and overseas marketing, spread improved
breeds and develop feed-processing enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, foreign investment has played an important role in
the development of the province's animal husbandry. A joint
venture -- involving 700 million yuan of investment by Chia Tai
Group Companies of Thailand and Jilin -- has set up farms for
raising chicken, factories to produce feed and meat processing
plants. In 1996, the joint venture accounted for seven billion
U.S. dollars in exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
