<HEADLINE> Indian Ocean Races Not to Be Changed Despite Shark Scare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Organisers said on Monday
that despite three recent shark scares the five kilometer and 25
kilometer events in the Indian Ocean will go ahead as part of
January's World Swimming Championships in Perth, Australia.
</P>
<P>
Recently, three accidents were reported that sharks attacked
persons at Swanbourne and Cottesloe beaches, but injury was
reported.
</P>
<P>
The Western Australian Fisheries Department said there is no
need for panic, as such sightings were normal in November.
</P>
<P>
About 80 swimmers were expected to take part in the offshore
races, starting from Hillarys Boat Harbour, in the oceanside
suburb of Sorrento.
</P>
<P>
Kevin Holtom, co-ordinator of the ocean evevts, said a spotter
aircraft would be used as a cautionary measure and each competitor
would have a support boat. 
</P>
