<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia, Pacific Make Progress on Social Development: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel
Ramos said here today that Asian and Pacific economies have made
substantial progress in the sphere of social development.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony of the Fifth Asian and Pacific
Ministerial Conference on Social Development, Ramos said the
region's economic dynamism during the final decade has not only
raised many economies to the threshold of economic modernization,
but has also significantly improved the well-being of millions of
people.
</P>
<P>
"Poverty incidence has been dramatically reduced in many
countries. And just as important, education and health levels have
improved across the board -- enhancing the efficiency,
productivity and equality of labor in many economies," he said.
</P>
<P>
For the part of the Philippines, Ramos said the government has
formulated policies and programs addressing poverty, unemployment
and underemployment, social inequity and family disunity.
</P>
<P>
The country's poverty rate has been reduced from 40 percent in
1991 to 34 percent in 1996 while the life expectancy has been
raised from 66.6 years to 69.4 years and the infant mortality rate
has decreased from 52 per 1,000 live births in 1993 to 45.8 in
1997, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Rising employment has come hand in hand with our economic
recovery and growth during the past four years. The unemployment
rate dropped from 9.8 percent in 1992 to 7.7 percent as of the
first semester of 1997," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, significant progress does not mean that Asian and
Pacific economies are not facing any problems and challenges, he
said, adding that in the Philippines, it is still hard to say
whether absolute poverty can be eradicated by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
The president urged Asian and Pacific economies to make more
sound policies, launch more appropriate programs, devote more
resources and strengthen cooperation with each other to secure a
better future for the region.
</P>
<P>
During the ministerial conference organized by the UN Economic
and Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific, delegates of 26
economies will review the region's social development situation
and prospects, examine progress made by the economies in achieving
social development goals and discuss measures to accelerate social
development in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
