<HEADLINE> New Port In East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Sandu'ao Harbor in east China's
Fujian Province, potentially the largest port on the western
shores of the Pacific Ocean, has taken shape over five years of
development.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary design and hydrologic and geological surveys have
been completed, and the initial port with a handling capacity of
20,000 tons has been constructed.
</P>
<P>
The second stage will include the construction of six major
infrastructure projects involving ports, highways and a water
plant, as well as a transformer substation, and post and
communications facilities.
</P>
<P>
Plans also call for the development of local tourism resources,
raising production and increasing the annual export volume for
stone to 50 million U.S. dollars over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
The Sandu'ao Development Zone, which will cover 124 sq.km., was
approved in 1992. Sandu'ao Harbor was granted approval to open to
the outside world in 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
