<DOCNO> XIE19971110.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Companies Get Equal Treatment in Shenzhen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 7 (Xinhua) -- Foreigners in Shenzhen, the
pioneer of China's reform and opening to the outside world, have
seen their business jacked up and living cost cut down since
granted the equal treatment as Chinese companies at the beginning
of the year.
</P>
<P>
The equal treatment measure taken by Shenzhen was aimed at
providing a fair competitive environment for foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 100 foreign companies, which engage in high-tech
products and agricultural products manufacturing, are allowed to
sell their products inside China. Formerly, most or all of their
products had to be exported.
</P>
<P>
The foreign companies' electricity cost went down by 0.01 yuan
for one watt to 0.88 yuan, the same rate local companies pay.
</P>
<P>
To the city, however, the move means a reduction of 350 million
yuan in electric earnings this year, because foreign companies
consume 3.5 million kilowatts electricity a year.
</P>
<P>
Foreigners, also benefitting from the new equal policy, no
longer have to pay a higher rate than local people for park
entrance tickets, medical treatment, buying and renting houses and
other forms of service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
