<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Set Up 3rd Export Processing Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
decided to set up the third export processing zone (EPZ) at
Comilla, 90 kilometers from the capital, with a view to boost
export for rapid economic growth of the country, it was learned
today from the Board of Governors of the Bangladesh Export
Processing Zones Authority (BEPZA).
</P>
<P>
At present, there are only two EPZs (Chittagong and Dhaka) in
this South Asian country, and they are unable to cope with the
increasing demand from investors.
</P>
<P>
The decision was taken at the BEPZA's 14th meeting held Sunday
at the prime minister's office.
</P>
<P>
The proposed Comilla EPZ will be set up on the unused lands of
the Comilla Airport, where some 182.1 hectares of land has been
acquired for the purpose.
</P>
<P>
The land already acquired by the government is suitable for
establishing an EPZ, because it has infrastructural facilities and
scope for developing direct communication with the Chittagong
Port, according the BEPZA.
</P>
<P>
The BEPZA board of governors meeting also decided to set up a
central treatment plant for industrial wastes at the Dhaka EPZ and
discussed the progress in setting up another two EPZs at Ishwardi
and Mongla.
</P>
<P>
In 1997-98 fiscal year, a target has been fixed for exporting
goods worth 700 million US dollars from the two existing EPZs,
BEPZA governors' board secretary Moazzen Hossain Khan told the
meeting.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
