<P>
Camdessus made this announcement in Paris on Sunday, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus is expected to hold talks with Thailand's new
government led by Chuan Leekpai to secure a commitment by Thailand
to meet the IMF bailout conditions that will allow the country to
withdraw a second tranche loan of some 800 million US dollars from
it.
</P>
<P>
The IMF chief's trip to Thailand was scheduled immediately
after Thailand's Democrat Party leader Chuan was appointed the
23rd prime minister of the country on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Chuan has pledged to cooperate with the IMF, which provided a
loan package of 17.2 billion dollars to Thailand under some
conditions, including Thailand's commitment to streamline the
finance sector, carry out a floating baht system, cut the
government spending, and maintain the country's economic growth
and foreign exchange reserves at a proper level.
</P>
<P>
After being appointed Thailand's new prime minister on Sunday,
Chuan also vowed to do his best to revive confidence of investors,
solve the problems of ailing finance firms, stabilize the baht,
promote foreign investment, and boost exports.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus is also scheduled to visit Indonesia this week.
