<HEADLINE> Asian Ministerial Meeting on Social Development Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Ministers from 26 Asian and
Pacific economies gathered here today to assess the progress made
in achieving social development goals they set three years ago.
</P>
<P>
During the fifth Asian and Pacific Ministerial Conference on
Social Development, the ministers and vice ministers, together
with delegates of some international and regional organizations,
will examine the implementation of the Agenda for Action on Social
Development in the region approved here in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The document was made in preparation for the World Summit for
Social Development in Copenhagen, Denmark in 1995. In the
document, 35 Asian and Pacific economies set specific and
time-bound goals and targets in poverty alleviation, employment
expansion and the social integration of vulnerable groups
including the disabled.
</P>
<P>
The participants are also expected to review the social
development situation and prospects for the region into the next
century and adopt a ministerial declaration introducing ways and
methods to accelerate social development in the region.
</P>
<P>
The two-day conference was organized by the UN Economic and
Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific and hosted by the
Philippine government. To prepare for it, a senior officials'
meeting was held here from 5 to 8 November.  
</P>
</TEXT>
