<DOCNO> XIE19971110.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Currency Must Keep Link with U.S. Dollar, Says Tung Chee Hwa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong dollar must be and
will continue to be linked with the U.S. dollar, Tung Chee Hwa,
Chief Executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
reaffirmed here today.
</P>
<P>
Describing it "a fundamental issue", Tung said that there is
absolutely no need for Hong Kong to change such a link.
</P>
<P>
Tung predicted that once Hong Kong has got over the current
economic turmoil, its recovery would be faster than any of the
surrounding economies.
</P>
<P>
The Chief Executive was speaking at the opening of a one-day
economic cooperation meeting of Hong Kong, Shanghai and Osaka here
this morning. Experts and executives from the "three most
important cities in Asia", as Tung put it, will discuss and share
their ideas on the economic future and regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Tung cited strong economic fundamentals, continuous economic
expansion of five percent, low unemployment rate of 2.5 percent,
the world's fourth largest foreign exchange reserve of 88 billion
U.S. dollars, a conservative financial management and a budget
share this year of about two percent of Hong Kong's GDP as the
factors backing the decision.
</P>
<P>
He also recalled the vulnerability, fluctuation and uncertainty
of Hong Kong's economy before Hong Kong began to peg its currency
with the U.S. dollar some 14 years ago.
</P>
<P>
With 83 percent of Hong Kong's GDP from service sector, he
said, "a competitive devaluation of our currency will not make us
more competitive in the overall economic point of view."
</P>
<P>
The Chief Executive said he does not share the argument of a
proposed devaluation as it creates uncertainly, instead of
stability, especially on the economic fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
Tung Chee Hwa also mentioned Hong Kong's geographical position
which makes it possible to reach the outside world as well as
China's mainland, "which is unique and other cities can not
match."
</P>
<P>
He admitted that the comparative lift of rates to maintain Hong
Kong's competitiveness is painful to many including those who had
invested into the stock market.
</P>
<P>
With these being "short-term pains", Tung said that as soon as
it is overcome, Hong Kong's recovery would be faster than all the
other economies around us and Hong Kong will surely achieve its
goal of making it more competitive.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
