<HEADLINE> Annan Says Crisis in Iraq "Serious" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, November 9 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary
General Kofi Annan Sunday said he would try to find a diplomatic
solution to the serious crisis in Iraq, and urged Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein to cooperate with U.N. arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who returned to the U.N. headquarters in New York one
day earlier from his meeting with Latin American leaders in
Venezuela, met the three emissaries he sent to Baghdad last week
to meet with Iraqi leaders for a solution to the conflict on
U.N. arms inspections.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief told reporters that the situation in Iraq
remained "serious."
</P>
<P>
"It is serious; no one should underestimate it," he added.
</P>
<P>
Annan confirmed that he had received a letter brought to him
from Saddam Hussein but declined to disclose any details.
</P>
<P>
U.N. officials said that Baghdad's reply was not an
enthusiastic "yes" to the U.N. request to cooperate with the
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Iraq reportedly turned back the U.N. inspection team including
Americans on Sunday for the seventh time, a day before the U.N.
Security Council is scheduled to meet on the controversy.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. inspectors are trying to verify whether Iraq has
destroyed its long-range missiles and biological, chemical and
nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration has repeatedly warned that Baghdad
could face military action or economic sanctions if it continues
to block the U.N. inspectors from its weapons facilities.
</P>
<P>
Annan said that he would meet the Security Council on Monday to
brief it on the failed diplomatic mission, and hoped a diplomatic
solution could be reached next week.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Secretary General said that he also expected to meet
Iraq's Deputy Prime Minister Tarik Aziz sometime early next week
in New York.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
