<DOCNO> XIE19971110.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Economy Recovers Strongly: Central Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan economy has
recovered strongly in 1997 from the prevailing depression in 1996
with all key indicators showing favorable trends, according to the
latest economic condition report of the Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
The bank was quoted today by the local press as saying
available production data for the first eight months indicated the
country could achieve a gross domestic product (GDP) growth rate
of close to 6.3 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The report, the State of the Economy, said investor confidence
increased because of corporate profitability and a favorable
economic environment.
</P>
<P>
The average Colombo consumer price index declined from 16
percent in December 1996 to 11.7 percent in September 1997.
</P>
<P>
An improvement in domestic food supply, higher imports and a
slowdown of monetary expansion were the main reasons for the
decrease of inflation, the report stated.
</P>
<P>
Export-oriented manufacturing sector has grown faster. Export
of textiles and garments rose by 23 percent during the first eight
months while total industrial exports went up by 20 percent, the
bank pointed out.
</P>
<P>
It went on to say Sri Lanka has been able to maintain its
export competitiveness due to the depreciation of the rupee
against the U.S. dollar by 5.1 percent in the first three
quarters.
</P>
<P>
The tea sector continued to enjoy attractive prices in
international markets. The January to August export prices were 11
percent higher than the corresponding period last year while the
Colombo auction prices jumped by 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
The bank said telecommunication services expanded with the
number of subscribers soaring by 29 percent during the first nine
months.
</P>
<P>
Port services continued to grow with the arrival of ships
increasing by 17 percent and the volume of container traffic
rising 36 percent, it added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
