<DOCNO> XIE19971110.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cases of Malaria on Rise in South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Some 1,300 South Koreans were
stricken with malaria as of the end of October this year, almost
quadruple the total infected for all of last year, according to
statistics from the Health and Welfare Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers accounted for 83 percent of the 1305 victims. Experts
explain that solders are especially vulnerable to mosquitos during
night-time duties, when the insects prefer to feed.
</P>
<P>
Malaria, a kind of infectious disease, which is most often
transmitted by the bite of the infected Anopheles mosquito, once
declared eradicated in South Korea, now is rapidly rising.
</P>
<P>
Since 1979, malaria had not been reported in South Korea and
WHO once declared the country malaria-free. However, the epidemic
mysteriously appeared again in 1993 when a soldier stationed in
Paju, a city near the Demilitarized Zone (DMZ), was found infected.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the number of cases has risen, with two in 1994,
107 in 1995 and 356 last year.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has been conducting research since last year - on
antibodies, or the body's immune system, of residents living in
malaria-stricken areas, and on the mosquitos, - to find out the
cause and why it has appeared only in front-line areas.
</P>
<P>
"Unlike other types of malaria, the strain now appearing in
South Korea, Vivax Malaria, is not fatal," said a ministry
official, "Historically, no one has died of it here."
</P>
<P>
Some experts say that a big flood in Yonchon nearby the DMZ
about two years ago and global warming have had a big hand in
creating conditions for the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
There is speculation that blood transfusions are to blame. The
ministry banned blood donations by civilians who resided in areas
near the DMZ, and personnel discharged from military front-line
service during the last two years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
