<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Chuan Faces Tough Tasks Ahead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Democrat Party leader Chuan
Leekpai returned to power on Sunday, but he will have to face
tough tasks ahead, in particular the economic woes in the country
which pushed his predecessor Chavalit Yongchaiyudh to resign.
</P>
<P>
Chuan won a hard victory after a fierce race with Chatichai
Choonhavan, leader of the Chart Pattana (national development)
Party. Yet he would find his road ahead harder as the country
remains in a deep economic slowdown which is drawing concerns both
domestically and internationally.
</P>
<P>
Thailand is expected to see a slower economic growth this year.
Caretaking Finance Minister Kosit Panpiemras last Friday predicted
that Thailand's economic growth this year will be 0.6 percent,
lower than 2.5 percent predicted early this year. The latest
prediction is also far lower than the figure of 6.8 percent last
year.
</P>
<P>
Inflation is predicted as high as 12 percent compared with a
9.5 percent forecast earlier this year due to the weaker baht,
which tumbled to a record low of more than 41 baht to one US
dollar.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's exports are forecast to rise by 3.2 percent in value
from last year, but the increase is meager, mainly due to the
calculation under the depreciated rate of the baht against the US
dollar.
</P>
<P>
The Stock Exchange of Thailand index last weekend posted 493.04
points, compared with more than 1,400 points in February last
year.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's current economic slowdown may be traced back to last
year when the country saw almost no increase in its exports, an
economic growth rate of 6.8 percent, a declining stock market and
the sluggish property sector.
</P>
<P>
Banharn Silpa-Archa was forced to resign from the premiership
and dismiss parliament to hold a general election on November 17
last year. But Banharn's departure was mainly due to failed power
maneuvers within the coalition government and not to economic
problems.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit Yongchaiyudh took over the post from Banharn after
winning the election with two seats more in the lower house than
the Chuan-led Democrat Party, yet he also inherited the problems
facing the country.
</P>
<P>
The Chavalit coalition government early introduced measures,
including injections of large sums of funds, to prop up the
troubled property sector and the declining stock market, but the
measures seemed generating less positive and long-lasting
responses from the markets than expected.
</P>
<P>
Until May this year, the looming liquidity problem in
Thailand's financial sector began to float onto the surface and
the stability of the baht began to shake. The Chavalit government
then chose to mobilize its foreign exchange reserves to defend the
baht.
</P>
<P>
However, despite the initial success in defending the baht, the
government found that the country's limited foreign reserves could
not win the battle in the long run, so it chose to float the baht
and seek financial aid from the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
Yet, floating the baht is a measure that the previous
governments had never chosen over the past 13 years and the IMF
aid is conditional.
</P>
<P>
The baht slumped to a record low of more than 41 baht against
the US dollar earlier this month, dealing a fresh blow to the
already shaken confidence of investors, which is believed to be
the most direct factor that forced Chavalit finally to decide to
leave his post.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Chuan put the restoration of investors' confidence
and the stabilization of the baht as the tasks of priority of his
government immediately after he was appointed as the country's new
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Also, Chuan has to face a coalition government which might
consist of as many as seven or eight political parties. How he
could manage to handle the multi-party coalition will also test
the statesman's talent.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, Chuan is now Thailand's favorite choice for a new
prime minister and the public opinion widely praised him as a
person of honesty and principle. As Thailand is predicted to enter
the most difficult period next year, Chuan has no choice but to
do, as he said, his best to refresh the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971110.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
