<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Census on Migrant Population Aids Beijing Policymaking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Beijing officials will use new
census information on the city's migrant population to develop
plans for the city's economic future.
</P>
<P>
The census of non-Beijing natives, which started November 1,
will end on November 15.
</P>
<P>
During a recent interview with Xinhua, an official in charge of
the census said Beijing has nearly 13 million natives but the
local government has to take into consideration of the impact of
millions of migrants when planning for the supply of food, coal
and gas, transport, public health and family planning.
</P>
<P>
The current census is the first of its kind in China. In
Beijing, the migrant population refers to those who live and work
in the capital but do not have permanent regitration cards issued
by the local police.
</P>
<P>
A 1994 survey shows that Beijing has 3 million migrant
residents.
</P>
<P>
The official said the government urgently needs to discuss ways
to make better arrangement for non-Beijing natives who can
contribute to the development of the city.
</P>
<P>
Migrant people play an active role in Beijing's urban
construction, economic development and services for local
residents, the official said. The migrants have become an
important part of Beijing's economic and social development, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that more than 40 percent of construction
workers in the city are migrants, who also represent a majority in
the textile, sanitation and coal mining industries as well as
service sectors such as clothing and vegetable sales and child
care.
</P>
<P>
Migrants also are among those who have made outstanding
achievement in science, technology, commerce, investment and the
arts, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that one-third of Beijing's retail purchases
is made by non-Beijing natives.
</P>
<P>
Results of the census, including the total number, location,
structure, cultural backgrounds and professions of the migrant
population, will be made public at the end of December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971110.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama Canal Sees Deficit for Two Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Panama City, November 9 (Xinhua) -- The Panama Canal saw a
deficit of up to 3.9 million U.S. dollars in the last two years,
the Panama Canal Commission said.
</P>
<P>
A recent statistics released by the commission showed deficits
of 2 million dollars in fiscal 1997 that ended in September and
1.9 million dollars in fiscal 1996.
</P>
<P>
The deficit was mainly caused by the huge amount of wages for
the employees, the commission said. It paid 356 million dollars
as wages this year.
</P>
<P>
Although the transit fee charged for crossing the canal was
raised by 8.2 percent in January, and starting in July the fee
collected was counted on the number of containers, the income
still fell short of expenditure as the number of ships and the
tonnage crossing the canal dropped, the commission said.
</P>
<P>
By the end of September, the number of ships crossing the canal
totalled 13,700, 563 ships less than last year and the tonnage was
11 million less. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
