<HEADLINE> Diarrhea, Malaria Kill 80 in Irian Jaya, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Diarrhea and malaria have
killed at least 80 villagers in a week in Indonesia's easternmost
province of Irian Jaya, where drought and a lack of clean water
continue to threaten the lives of thousands, reports said.
</P>
<P>
The death toll from diarrhea in the Merauke district in
southern Irian Jaya has claimed from 58 to 74 lives in less than a
week as smoke from smoldering fires continued to hamper relief
efforts, Antara News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
In the mountainous region of central Irian Jaya, six people
were reported to have died from malaria over the past week,
according to Jaya Wijaya district chief Jo Buas Wenas.
</P>
<P>
Wenas warned that malaria was spreading rapidly and threatening
the lives of 90,000 people in the district, where more than 400
people this year have died from drought-related diseases and
famine.
</P>
<P>
The latest deaths bring the number of fatalities to more than
500 this year throughout Irian Jaya where most of the 2 million
inhabitants adhere to a traditional way of life and depend on what
they grow for survival.  
</P>
</TEXT>
