<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Boost Rural Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka is to launch a
five-year rural development program to boost economic activity in
selected undeveloped districts this month, Plan Implementation
Ministry sources said today.
</P>
<P>
The project, "Rural Economic Advancement Program", combines all
the previous programs for rural development funded by
international donor agencies, such as the Asian Development Bank
and the European Union, S.L. Seneviratne, secretary of the Plan
Implementation Ministry, said.
</P>
<P>
The program, which covers 15 selected districts in Sri Lanka,
targets employment for 150,000 people in rural areas and domestic
savings of 450 million Rupees (7.5 million U.S. dollars) to be
generated by 400,000 families.
</P>
<P>
It includes three major components -- market-based farm
enterprises, rural non-farm enterprises and village development.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, land will be cultivated with high-value
commercial crops and production facilities and processing units
will be improved for better agricultural output.
</P>
<P>
Seneviratne added the government has allocated a sum of 20
million Rupees (330,000 dollars) for the initial stage of the
program.
</P>
</TEXT>
