<HEADLINE> Police Find Cause of Food Poisoning in Fujian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Half-cooked fast-food was the
cause of a food-poisoning case involving more than 200 students
from a medical school, according to police in eastern China's
Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
Students at the Fujian Medical School went to a nearby
restaurant for snacks after a sports meeting on November 2.
</P>
<P>
Some of the students began to have symptoms such as headaches,
stomach-aches, vomiting and diarrhea and were sent to
hospital. All were doing well after receiving medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
With the help of the local health authorities, police found
that the food poisoning was caused by germs in the restaurants'
half-cooked seafood, eggs and meat.
</P>
<P>
The owner of the restaurant has been detaineded by the local
police for investigation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
