<HEADLINE> International Population Meeting to be Held in Dhaka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The 3rd annual meeting of the
Board of Governors of the Partners in Population and Development,
an inter-governmental alliance of 10 developing countries, will be
held in Dhaka from November 17 to 19, an official release said
here today.
</P>
<P>
The partners' initiative was launched at the 1994 International
Conference on Population and Development (ICPD) in Cairo by
Bangladesh, Colombia, Egypt, Indonesia, Kenya, Mexico, Morocco,
Thailand, Tunisia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The 10-partner countries are internationally recognized as
having developed effective population policies, programs and
services, and as being strongly committed to the implementation of
the ICPD program of action, the release stated.
</P>
<P>
The conference, to be prepared by a meeting of the partners'
executive committee, will bring together ministers, top population
policy and health specialists from the 10 countries. The
conference is expected to be opened by Bangladeshi President
Shahabuddin Ahmed.
</P>
<P>
The partners' executive committee has also invited other
developing countries, international agencies and NGOs interested
in the implementation of improved reproductive health and family
planning programs through expanded South-South Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Behind the birth of the alliance was the concept of maximizing
benefits South-South collaboration, articulated in the 20-year
program of action which was endorsed by 180 countries at Cairo.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first time that an international alliance has been
formed specifically to expand and improve South-South
Collaboration in the fields of family planning and reproductive
health," said Balla Musa Silla, acting executive director of the
partners initiative.
</P>
<P>
The Dhaka meeting of the partners board, which follows similar
meetings in Harare in 1995 and in Mexico City in 1996, will also
review progress made so far by this South-South initiative, and
discuss the secretariat's operational plan for 1997-1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
