<HEADLINE> Shanghai Becomes Largest Japanese Business Partner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai has become the
largest Japanese business partner among all the major cities
around the world, with contractual investment from Japan hitting
3.1 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The metropolitan has set up 2,130 Japanese-funded enterprises
and nearly 400 representative offices, according to the city's
foreign investment commission official .
</P>
<P>
During the first half of this year, Shanghai replaced Hong Kong
for the first as the largest recipients of Japanese investment in
the world.
</P>
<P>
Since the late 1970s, Shanghai has made progress in cooperating
with Japan on a number of economic and technological projects,
such as Shanghai Baoshan Iron and Steel Company, the largest and
most advanced company of its kind in China. In the past decade,
both sides have joined hands in producing micro-electronics,
computers, color TVs and parts, and household apparatus.
</P>
<P>
Among the world's top 100 companies listed in "Fortune"
magazine of the United States, 11 Japanese companies have invested
in Shanghai, which include Hitachi, Mitsushita, Sony and Sharp.
</P>
<P>
In addition, local Japanese-funded projects are involved in
retail sales, foreign trade, financial and insurance
businesses. There are now 14 Japanese banks and insurance
companies who have set up offices in Shanghai. Two Sino-Japanese
joint trade companies have been approved to set up in the Pudong
New Area.
</P>
<P>
Japanese-funded enterprises now lead local overseas-funded
projects in export volume and business returns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
