<DOCNO> XIE19971110.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Irrigation Project Alleviates Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 10 (Xinhua) -- A large irrigation works in
Gansu Province is expected to lift 280,000 people out of poverty
and benefit more than one million people by the turn of the
century, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The Yindaruqin Project is a large-scale transbasin gravity
irrigation scheme, which diverts water form the Datong River in
Qinghai Province to Qinwangchuan Plain, about 60 km away from
Lanzhou, capital of Gansu Province.
</P>
<P>
After the main part of the project was completed in 1995, more
than 27,000 ha. of farmland had been irrigated, said Gu Qijie,
general engineer of the project.
</P>
<P>
He said the annual average precipitation in Qinwanchuan Plain
is 285 millimeters, but the annual evaporation reaches 1,888
millimeters. Because of the severe shortages of water and low
productivity, the grain output per ha. used to be only about 1,500
kg.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the project, the average per ha. output in the region
has been sharply increased to 9,000 kg.
</P>
<P>
By June this year, another 680 ha. of forest were established
as water supply improved. And more than 35,000 people moved to the
irrigated area, with 70 percent of newcomers setting up houses and
digging water cellars.
</P>
<P>
The Yindaruqin Project includes 884 km of feeder canals, main
canals and branch canals, with a length almost half of the Beijing
Hangzhou Grand Canal. It has 71 tunnels with a total length of 110
km, and is called the longest "underground canal" in China.
</P>
<P>
Investment in the project will exceed one billion yuan (120
million U.S. dollars), nearly half of it coming from World Bank
loans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971110.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
