<HEADLINE> Thirty Big US Investors Tour China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Thirty US institutional
investors managing 1.3 trillion U.S. dollars in assets toured Hong
Kong, Shanghai and Beijing last week to get a close look at the
Chinese investment environment in the wake of the severe financial
crisis in Southeast Asia, today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
It was the fourth time that JP Morgan Securities Asia Ltd had
held such a roadshow for investors of fixed-income bonds. Jointed
by 40 Asian and European fixed income investors, the roadshow
began in Hong Kong last Monday, and was scheduled to continue on
today to Seoul, the final destination.
</P>
<P>
The investors met a number of officials from the Ministry of
Finance, State Administration of Foreign Exchange, China
International Trust and Investment Corp and policy banks on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the dialogue that we will initiate here will be a
step towards developing a clear understanding of what is happening
here in Asia and improving Asia's access to the international
credit markets," said Martin Mastsui, head of JP Morgan's fixed
income business in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Their concerns included: relations between the interior and
Hong Kong; progress of State-owned enterprises' restructuring;
whether China can continue its current high economic growth with
its low inflation rate; and to what extent China's enterprises'
openness could be improved.
</P>
<P>
Matsui said that compared with other Asian countries, China was
a relatively stronger performer which would be a favourite target
for international investors.
</P>
<P>
JP Morgan plays one of the top roles in the world commercial
banking and investment banking business, serving for more than 150
years as financial advisor, underwriter and lender to governments,
institutions and major international firms. 
</P>
