<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila to Present Financial Services Offer to WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines will present
today its offer to the World Trade Organization on a proposed
financial services agreement in hopes of sending good signals and
obtaining reciprocal concessions from other countries.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank Managing Director Amando Tetangco said the
country's offer -- with a commitment to allow foreigners to own up
to 51 percent equity in investment and insurance companies and up
to 60 percent in banks by 2002 -- was approved by the Government
Tariff Committee Friday.
</P>
<P>
With the country's offer, Tetangco said, "we hope to get more
concessions (in financial services). We're looking at the other
countries and encourage them to improve their offers as well."
</P>
<P>
The country's offer was an improvement from its
across-the-board commitment of only 40 percent in 1995 and 49
percent equity cap this year.
</P>
<P>
The WTO will start one-week negotiations today to prepare for
the targeted signing of the WTO financial services agreement by
December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
