<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia's Economy Recovery Advances Tourism to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 10 (Xinhua) - Prosperous trade and economic
exchanges have greatly enhanced Sino-Russian tourism in
Heilongjiang Province in recent years, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The number of overseas travellers to northeastern Heilongjiang,
which shares a 3,000-km-long border with Russia, increased 60
percent to 259,000 last year, said Bo Xiru, deputy director of
Heilongjiang Tourism Administration (HTA).
</P>
<P>
In the first eight months of this year, the number increased by
42 percent over the same period last year, with 215,900 tourists
flowing in. The industry generated 61 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The number of travellers form Russia to Heilongjiang is
expected to exceed 250,000 by the end of this year, Bo predicted.
</P>
<P>
Most Russians travelling to Heilongjiang are on shopping sprees
-- purchasing food, clothes, electronics and other necessities.
</P>
<P>
Russia's recovering economy has led to an increased number of
Russians visiting the province, Bo said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the province will spend 230 million yuan (27
million U.S. dollars) to improve Heilongjiang's tourist facilities
and highways.
</P>
<P>
He continued: "We tightened the administrations on
qualification, charges and quality of services of local tourist
agencies serving Sino-Russian tourism."
</P>
<P>
"Only agencies of strong economic basis are granted permission
to conduct business in this field."
</P>
<P>
A tourist agency has to pay 600,000 yuan (70,588 U.S. dollars)
security deposit to the HTA to receive a permission.
</P>
<P>
The money will be used as compensation if a complaint is filed
against the agency by overseas tourists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971110.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 20 Weak Banks Likely To Merge In Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government's
decisive move to close 16 ailing banks early this month is
apparently a shock therapy as 20 banks have reportedly planned to
conduct merger and consolidation.
</P>
<P>
The liquidation will force weak banks to merge among themselves
or with larger ones, Thomas Suyatno, chairman of the Association
of Private National Banks said here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Merging would be the best alternative for weak banks to escape
a government closure order, local press today quoted Suyatno as
saying.
</P>
<P>
He estimated that at least 20 banks would merge in the near
future to solve their financial difficulties. But he could not
specify which banks would merge.
</P>
<P>
He said the government's decision to shut the 16 banks, as part
of the International Monetary Fund's economic reform package, was
an impartial move and would prompt other banks to consolidate to
prevent themselves from being forced into liquidation too.
</P>
<P>
According to the government regulation on bank liquidation,
Bank Indonesia, the central bank, has rights in overlapping the
authority of shareholders.
</P>
<P>
Bank Indonesia drew up criteria or check lists on the country's
239 banks before it made the decision, and those which did not
meet the criteria were closed down, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
