<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-based National Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 10 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers are as follows:
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Russian President Boris Yeltsin arrived in Beijing yesterday
evening by special aircraft, starting his two-day state visit to
China as guest of his Chinese counterpart Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
This is Yeltsin's third state visit to China. The two heads of
state are expected to hold their fifth summit Monday.
</P>
<P>
Upon arrival, Yeltsin told reporters at the airport: "This is a
big success. The border demarcation alone made it worth coming
here." In addition, he added, he will meet Chinese leaders and may
sign a number of agreements.
</P>
<P>
-- The newspaper front-paged a speech delivered by Premier Li
Peng last Friday on the second-phase immigration for the
construction of Three Gorges Project.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- The State Council has recently approved the third-phase
construction of the huge Shenhua Project for coal shipment in
north China.
</P>
<P>
The third-phase construction of Shenhua, a passage to transport
coal from western to eastern China, includes a 586-km railway from
Shuozhou city in Shanxi province to Huanghua city in Hebei
province and a port in Huanghua with an annual handling capacity
of 30 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The third phase of the project is scheduled to be completed by
2005.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Vice Premier Li Lanqing held talks with visiting
Russian First Deputy Prime Minister Boris Nemtsov in Beijing
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Li told Nemtsov that the Chinese government pays close
attention to President Boris Yeltsin's China visit. President
Jiang Zemin and Yeltsin will hold their fifth summit today and
discuss prospects for the development of bilateral relations and
major international issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The successful operation of damming the world's third
longest river, Yangtze River, marked an important stride for China
in its quest to tame its longest river. Reason: To control the
river's devastating floods that occur every ten years , and tap
its rich water and hydro-electricity resources for the coming 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
-- The site chosen for the construction of China's largest
nuclear station in Lianyungang, a port city in east China's
Jiangsu province, has passed a China National Nuclear Safety
Administration test. That allows the state project to organize
feasibility studies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
