<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Passes Legislation to Accelerate Lifesaving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 9 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate Sunday
approved a bill that will bring basic changes to the Food and Drug
Administration (FDA) and speed up the approval of lifesaving drugs.
</P>
<P>
The House of Representatives was expected to agree soon to the
bill.
</P>
<P>
The bill expands patient access to new drugs for
life-threatening illnesses, provides for accelerated approval of
some drugs and medical devices and allows the Health and Human
Services secretary to accredit independent third-party groups to
speed up reviews of low-risk devices.
</P>
<P>
It also reauthorizes a five-year program under which fees paid
by drug companies have gone to hire 600 new reviewers who have
helped cut the backlog in new medicine approvals. Incentives are
included for developing and testing medicines for children.
</P>
<P>
Senator Edward Kennedy, who held up the legislation for weeks
this fall while fighting for changes in provisions he thought were
detrimental to consumers, called the final bill "a victory for
public health, for patients, and for industry alike."
</P>
<P>
The bipartisan agreement came after extensive negotiations on a
number of controversial issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
