<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Infrastructure Costs Seen to Surge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 10 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is
expected to revise its capital spending pattern next year as the
cheaper peso is expected to drive up the cost of infrastructure
projects with imported inputs.
</P>
<P>
In a report published today, Socioeconomic Planning Secretary
Cielito Habito said the government would need an additional 5.7
billion pesos (164 million U.S. dollars) next year to fund all of
projects in its 1998 infrastructure program.
</P>
<P>
The peso depreciation has resulted in more expensive imported
inputs, which are "almost always" needed for local infrastructure
projects, Habito said.
</P>
<P>
The peso has lost more than 30 percent of its value against the
U.S. dollar since its de facto devaluation on July 11 this year.
</P>
<P>
The government's infrastructure and capital spending is
projected to increase by 633 million pesos (18.2 million dollars)
for every one peso depreciation, according to Habito.
</P>
<P>
The peso devaluation will force the government to increase by
5.7 billion pesos in the required infrastructure and capital
outlays in the 1998 infrastructure budget, Habito said.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposed 1998 budget, the government's infrastructure
program gets 140 billion pesos (4 billion dollars), compared with
the 103 billion pesos (3 billion dollars) allocated for 1997.
</P>
<P>
To minimize the impact of the more expensive dollar, Habito
said project managers, if possible, should try to look for locally
produced materials as an alternative.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971110.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> United States Qualifies for World Cup Finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 9 (Xinhua) -- The United States defeated
Canada 3-0 in a World Cup qualifier in Vancouver on Sunday,
securing its berth in the 1998 World Cup finals in France.
</P>
<P>
With Jamaica drew El Salvador 2-2 in San Salvador, the match
between the United States and El Salvador next Sunday will just be
a celebratory festival.
</P>
<P>
Five minutes into the first half, Roy Wegerle raced down the
left side and sent a low rolling cross to Claudio Reyna, who
kicked the ball into the net.
</P>
<P>
Canada had the majority of possession throughout the game, but
rarely looked dangerous. As time wore on, Canada pushed forward
and exposed itself to counterattack when Wegerle took advantage.
</P>
<P>
Wegerle took a pass from midfield and moved in unmarked on the
Canadian goal, calmly scoring with a low shot to send the
Americans to the World Cup finals for the sixth time.
</P>
<P>
In the closing seconds, Wegerle scored the third to add to the
celebration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
